<p>It‚Äôs a strange scene! It wasn‚Äôt used in <em>2.0</em>; it was based on the originally scripted finale, which followed episode 23 much more closely and was changed very late in production. Shinji Higuchi drew the storyboard, and made an interesting comment in the CRC interviews; <a href="http://img84.imageshack.us/img84/4537/higuchi.jpg">here</a> is the excerpt. The storyboard is a version, I think, of <a href="http://img189.imageshack.us/img189/2339/72066859.jpg">this scene</a> from episode 23 of the series.</p>
</blockquote>
</section>
<section id="higuchi-interview" class="level3">
<h3>Higuchi interview</h3>
<p><code>Higuchi:</code> When I watched the preview screening, it was [the Asuka possession scene] that shocked me the most. The scene was supposed to be cruel, with Asuka becoming ‚Äúcorroded‚Äù and losing her face, but the [final] treatment had become incredibly gentle.</p>
<p>‚Äî In the first scenario, her fortune was to be pierced by a number of ultra-fine needles.</p>
<p><code>Higuchi:</code> So it was like the image of a ‚Äúhedgehog‚Äù. The fact that the needles were directed towards the interior meant that Asuka was becoming intropunitive [self-punishing].</p>
<p>‚Äî Therefore the scenario unfolds with Kaworu‚Äôs address: ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs not like you‚Äù. In Higuchi-san‚Äôs storyboard, the detached skin also becomes a face and addresses [Asuka]. The horror resembles <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kazuo%20Umezu" title="Wikipedia: Kazuo Umezu">Kazuo Umezu</a>‚Äôs ‚ÄúNikumen‚Äù, but from what image did this ‚Äúpeeling off‚Äù come from?</p>
<p><code>Higuchi:</code> The order was, ‚Äúsomething like ‚Äò<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/plastination" title="Wikipedia: plastination">plastination</a>.‚Äô‚Äù</p>
<p>‚Äî That‚Äôs used in <a href="http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/fl20060521x2.html" title="FATAL ATTRACTION: Vision from the other side">‚ÄúMysteries of the Human Body‚Äù</a><a href="#fn31" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref31"><sup>31</sup></a>. Dissected, three-dimensional objects made by pouring resin into donated bodies, right?</p>
<p><code>Higuchi:</code> Right. Here, I was thinking only of something that people would hate. Up to then there had been a somewhat ‚Äúpoka-poka‚Äù mood. Thinking ‚Äúthis ‚Äòhomeroom drama‚Äô is not Eva!‚Äù, I wanted to confront [the audience] with something hateful. In actuality, from the point of view of the story, from that point on ‚Äúhell‚Äù begins and that sort of happiness does not endure. ‚ÄúEva‚Äù is really like this; that ‚Äúpoka-poka‚Äù atmosphere will descend into chaos! I put that sort of feeling of ill-will into my drawing.</p>
<p>When that sort of shocking thing didn‚Äôt happen, I thought that the development by which the happiness that had [been portrayed] up to that point changes to tragedy probably wouldn‚Äôt occur. As for the Asuka of ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù, it was a situation where the entire team was at odds. This being the case, I thought this [scene?] was an absolute ‚Äúdeath flag‚Äù. I thought about a cruelty worse than death, and this was the result.</p>
<p>‚Äî I thought that this ‚Äú‚ÄòNikumen‚Äô version‚Äù had been selected [to be used]. It was also used in Tsurumaki-san‚Äôs storyboards, and during the recording sessions I have a memory of it being recorded.</p>
<p><code>Higuchi:</code> As for when and how it was changed, I don‚Äôt know, but probably the malice [I felt] when I drew the scene was too much for people to see up front.</p>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=404501#404501">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=404501#404501</a></p>
<p><a href="http://img101.imageshack.us/img101/8995/higuchi2.jpg">http://img101.imageshack.us/img101/8995/higuchi2.jpg</a></p>
<pre><code>Early Provisional Draft Storyboard / Shinji HIGUCHI
Corresponding to section C-1367 of the completed work.
A scene where Shinji leaves Tokyo-3.
For provisional draft storyboards, cut numbers are omitted.

Mari: I'm not interested in boys who run away with their tail between their legs...!
      Are you stupid? [_Anta baka_?] One person almost died? What? Are you a coward?
      Don't take [me?] for granted[?]. Instead, I'll only thank you if you fight.
      Your expression - like you alone carry all the burdens on your shoulders - looks idiotic!
      ... is what Asuka-chan would say if she was here. / MARI: It's not the case that you
      could become God because you piloted Eva. There are people you can save, and people you can't.</code></pre>
<p>‚Äî [‚Ä¶] As for Mari, there is a scene where she has a conversation with Shinji after he parts from Misato. She imitates Asuka‚Äôs manner of speaking there, right? Afterwards, at the climax of the battle where Unit-01 grows wings, she is staring at it from a distance‚Ä¶</p>
<p><code>Higuchi:</code> If I had to say, I‚Äôd say she was like a female version of Kaworu.</p>
<hr/>
<p><a href="http://img816.imageshack.us/img816/7936/higuchi3.jpg">http://img816.imageshack.us/img816/7936/higuchi3.jpg</a></p>
<pre><code>Early Provisional Draft Storyboard / Shinji HIGUCHI
Corresponding to section C-1456 and following of the completed work.
A scene where Eva Unit-02 battles the 10th Angel in the Geofront.
An unconscious Asuka is restrained within the Entry Plug.</code></pre>
<p>‚Äî [‚Ä¶] Mari does not pilot Eva-02 during the climax in your June 2007 storyboard.</p>
<p><code>Higuchi:</code> That‚Äôs right, that‚Äôs right. We had an unconscious, ‚Äúpuppet/doll-like‚Äù Asuka riding in Unit-02, right?</p>
<hr/>
<figure>
<img height="1305" src="../images/eva/2010-crc/higuchi4.jpg" title="http://evazone.org/AME/CRC/higuchi4.jpg" width="1991"/>
</figure>
<pre><code>Early Provisional Draft Storyboard / Shinji HIGUCHI
Corresponding to section C-1676 and following of the completed work.
A scene where the 10th Angel invades Command Center No. 1 of Nerv HQ.
The HQ control tower retracts and gun turrets appear, firing upon the Angel.</code></pre>
<p>‚Äî Only, if we look at the first storyboards they are not completely the same [as the original episode 19]. Masayuki-san‚Äôs new idea ‚Äúthe command center becomes a battleship‚Äù was also inserted.</p>
<p><code>Higuchi:</code> ‚ÄúLet‚Äôs add artillery. The artillery of a battleship will emerge from the command center and fire. Tee-hee!‚Äù I received a proposal like that from Banchou [‚Äúdelinquent leader‚Äù] (Director Masayuki), so I drew the storyboard. But that development meeting took place much earlier than the ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù premiere, in a distant haze; I don‚Äôt know how long ago the conversation was.</p>
</section>
</section>
<section id="y≈çji-enokido" class="level2">
<h2>Y≈çji Enokido</h2>
<section id="background-1" class="level3">
<h3>Background</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=401918#401918">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=401918#401918</a> :</p>
<blockquote>
<p>As far as I understand it, [Y≈çji] [Enokido](!Wikipedia ‚ÄúYoji Enokido‚Äù) only worked on the movie for three days (at Atami). Probably the most important reason for getting him on board was to get an ‚Äúoutsider‚Äù to decide on the final cuts to be made (especially considering the fact, as the interview shows, that whoever had to make those decisions risked incurring the wrath of the others ^^). Afterwards, he didn‚Äôt know if his ideas would end up being used in the film or not. Later in the interview he says he was surprised to see a final sequence so close to the idea he proposed at Atami.</p>
<p>According to Enokido, Anno wrote the drafts of each Rebuild script by himself, and then consulted other people on various things afterwards. This is almost the reverse of how he worked on the series, where he described a plot, another writer produced the draft script, and finally Anno amended it.</p>
<p>Also according to Enokido, when Anno explained the ‚Äúbackground‚Äù (Ë£èË®≠ÂÆö) of Eva to him at Atami, it struck him as a continuation of what Anno had told him 16 years prior, when Enokido was writing for Eva. The mood at Atami was on the whole ‚Äúheavy‚Äù.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=399330#399330">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=399330#399330</a></p>
</section>
<section id="excerpt-1" class="level3">
<h3>Excerpt 1</h3>
<p><a href="http://evazone.org/AME/CRC/enokido1.png">http://evazone.org/AME/CRC/enokido1.png</a></p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Because ‚ÄúRebuild of Evangelion‚Äù is basically a reconstruction of the TV series, we presume that sooner or later Rei II will die. If Shinji-kun were to save Rei II it would mean a significant departure from the TV series. However, I believed that the last scene of the film had to be an earth-shattering climax. When I had this idea, it was impossible for me not to communicate it. I remember, on the third day [of the sessions], performing a solo play in front of everyone using hand gestures and body movements entitled ‚Äúthis is how it ends!‚Äù</p>
<p>‚Äî So, in this play, you performed actions like [Shinji] pulling [Rei] up and out [of the Angel]?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Right. Rei gets completely absorbed by the Angel. It‚Äôs just as though she has died and entered the netherworld. The audience is thinking that Rei is dead. Despite this, Shinji pilots Unit-01 again in order to save Rei. He cries out ‚ÄúAyanami!‚Äù and reaches forward, with an awful noise, through the front of the entry plug. He must establish some means of descending to the underworld. Finally, having grabbed (the unclothed) Rei‚Äôs hand, he pulls her out with a sudden movement. I feel I demonstrated this method of rescue with all my might. I completely transformed into Shinji. I think everyone was staring at me very coldly (laugh).</p>
</section>
<section id="excerpt-2" class="level3">
<h3>Excerpt 2</h3>
<p><a href="http://img10.imageshack.us/img10/9607/enokido2.png">http://img10.imageshack.us/img10/9607/enokido2.png</a></p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> ‚Ä¶ I felt the development of the second half of the TV series was incredible. Only, I was a little saddened by death of Rei II and her replacement by Rei III. For myself, I wanted that Rei who had repeatedly shared battles and encounters with Shinji to go on to the end. But the original scenario for ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù was, naturally, similar to the TV series, with Rei II self-destructing. On the morning of the third day [the production team] stayed together, I suddenly had the thought: ‚ÄúWhat if, in the final scene, Shinji happened to save Rei? ‚Ä¶ It would be incredible!‚Äù I worked myself up into a frenzy. Among the reasons for my enthusiasm was the recognition that this would completely overturn the expectations of the audience. When we speak of the most important ‚Äúcatharsis‚Äù provided by film, we might say that a film creates in the audience a sense that the characters are in danger, only to overturn it: we go from, ‚Äúthis character is in danger and surely will be badly hurt,‚Äù to ‚Äúit can‚Äôt be!‚Äù This constitutes, so to speak, a betrayal of the audience in the form of a sudden change. This ‚Äúsalvation‚Äù is the essence of the final scene.</p>
</section>
<section id="excerpt-3" class="level3">
<h3>Excerpt 3</h3>
<p><a href="http://img833.imageshack.us/img833/7826/enokido3.png">http://img833.imageshack.us/img833/7826/enokido3.png</a></p>
<p>[Note: I couldn‚Äôt quite work out the complete meaning of the first two sentences of this part without knowing the question Enokido was asked, so I left them out. They seem to relate to Anno and his assistant Todoroki ‚Äútaking over‚Äù the concept.]</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> ‚Ä¶ At that time I had only decided that Shinji would save Rei II. Afterwards, as I was performing and speaking more or less off the top of my head, I was entering a kind of trance state. As is typical of me, when I reached the climactic scene where [Shinji] cries ‚ÄúAyanami!‚Äù and begins to walk forward, just as I grabbed [Rei‚Äôs] hand and pulled [her] upwards, I suddenly came back to myself (laugh). ‚ÄúNow what happens?‚Äù I wondered. Now, in the film, when Shinji saves Rei, Kaworu-kun suddenly descends from heaven and impales him with a spear. When I was enthusiastically performing the ‚Äúsaving‚Äù scene, I couldn‚Äôt envision anything except Kaworu-kun stabbing me with something sharp and screaming ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs Enough! Act Responsibly!‚Äù (laugh)</p>
</section>
<section id="excerpt-4" class="level3">
<h3>Excerpt 4</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=466650#466650">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=466650#466650</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>‚ÄúIn short, Rei or someone else is caught in a desperate situation, a situation in which she absolutely cannot be saved. Shinji saves that person by means of an impossible method. I could not help wondering if the subtitle ‚ÄòThe Only Neat Thing To Do‚Äô implied such a scene, which achieves a cathartic reversal in a miraculous way‚Äù.</p>
</blockquote>
</section>
<section id="part-1-1" class="level3">
<h3>Part 1</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=399646#399646">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=399646#399646</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>A Request to Perfect the Screenplay</p>
</blockquote>
<p>‚Äî We received a strong demand from Anno-san that an interview with Enokido-san be included in the ‚ÄúComplete Works Collection‚Äù.</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> I see! If that‚Äôs the case, I‚Äôll answer enthusiastically (laughs).</p>
<p>‚Äî When we were gathering information from (Kazuya) Tsurumaki-san before the premiere, he told us that, in ‚Äúdestroying‚Äù Eva, your ideas are being incorporated everywhere<a href="#fn32" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref32"><sup>32</sup></a>. So we‚Äôre interested [to talk to you]. Do you remember the first occasion when [Anno] reached out to consult you?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> The document [produced as a result] still exists, so I brought it.</p>
<p>‚Äî Thank you. The story of the exact moment contains a strange ‚Äúpattern‚Äù, right?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> It was two years ago, so I think there are parts I‚Äôve started to forget. The first talk was in 2007, I think in late September or in October.</p>
<p>‚Äî So just following the premiere of ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Yeah. I went to see the movie, as a fan, soon after it opened. As I watched the preview trailer after the ending, I thought, ‚ÄúSo, from the next film forward we get new developments? This seems interesting‚Äù.</p>
<p>‚Äî You saw it as ‚Äúa complete outsider‚Äù, right? (smiles)</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> That night I received a call from ‚ÄúKhara-san‚Äù [Anno]. ‚ÄúWhat do you want to do for the second film?‚Äù ‚ÄúHuh? Me?‚Äù I remember a conversation along those lines.</p>
<p>‚Äî The fact that you had seen the first film just before that ‚Ä¶ it seems predestined, right? How did you view it?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> It was very interesting. I think it was a kind of conformation. To this day I still haven‚Äôt asked [Anno], but I wondered, ‚Äúwhy choose me for ‚ÄòBreak‚Äô‚Äù? I thought it was either because of my collaborations with Tsurumaki-san on <em>FLCL</em> and <em>Gunbuster 2</em>, or else I had been called because of my contributions to the scripts of the original ‚ÄúEva‚Äù series as a rotating staff member.</p>
<p>‚Äî When we were conducting other interviews, we got the feeling that the project reached a ‚Äúlimit‚Äù, followed by some kind of major change. It seems like Enokido-san‚Äôs ideas were relied on more than what had been developed previously.</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> When I was called, there were already scheduling pressures. At that time I also heard that two different versions of the last scene had been storyboarded and scrapped.</p>
<p>‚Äî That being the case, did you have the impression of seeing things from completely outside of the ‚ÄúRebuild‚Äù project?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Yes. Because I worked as a scriptwriter on four episodes of the original TV series, I am credited in the ‚ÄúRebuild‚Äù films as a ‚Äúscreenplay consultant‚Äù. However, I did no work at all on ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù, and at the time I was called to work on ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù, a complete draft of the film‚Äôs script already existed. As Anno said he wanted further changes, I was sent a copy of the script before a meeting between us was even arranged. So first of all I read the script, and found it very interesting.</p>
<p>‚Äî What sort of things seemed interesting?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> To begin with, considering that ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù has to recreate episodes one through six in less than two hours, I think they did an excellent job organizing the film and maintaining balance. The story development is the same; it‚Äôs okay if they crowd out the details. That being the case, when I thought about ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù, I expected that they would do a good job if they managed to cover episodes eight to thirteen or so. But when I realized they were attempting to treat everything up to episode twenty-three in one go, I couldn‚Äôt understand how they would do it. However, when I read the script, I saw how amazingly skillfully things had been organized. ‚ÄúJust as I expected!‚Äù I thought. ‚ÄúIndeed, if they do it like this, the entire series becomes a single episode‚Äù.</p>
<p>‚Äî And yet, despite doing so well, they had lost their bearings, and asked you to fix things?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Right‚Ä¶ I had received the impression that Mari‚Äôs character development was not yet complete. Furthermore, I think that there were parts that still retained the atmosphere of a ‚Äúsummary film‚Äù. Because an outside observer often sees further than the participants, I thought it would be good to begin by pointing out these sorts of things. I wrote an entire ‚Äúplan of organization‚Äù or ‚Äúplan of revision‚Äù; I believe it was this document here (Dated October 13; reproduced in CRC 2.0 pp.¬†236-237). To the extent it discusses the plot no changes are made; it‚Äôs a ‚Äúcompositional memo‚Äù. I submitted the memo shortly after the script arrived, and after that a meeting was arranged, but the location was not Khara-san‚Äôs studio. I was ordered, ‚ÄúCome to Atami!‚Äù and I was led away as though I were being abducted. It‚Äôs as one expects from ‚ÄúEva‚Äù, right? (laugh)</p>
<p>‚Äî That was the ‚ÄúAtami Retreat‚Äù, right?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> When I asked, ‚ÄúWhy Atami?‚Äù I was answered, ‚ÄúIf we are to arrange a proper meeting, we should go where the food is delicious‚Äù. That‚Äôs a very Anno-like proposal. As the script had already been written, there were not supposed to be any major changes, and so I had thought that when I sent the memo, that would be it. When we began the ‚ÄúAtami Retreat‚Äù on October 31st, I was wondering what on earth was going on.</p>
</section>
<section id="part-2-1" class="level3">
<h3>Part 2</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=400206#400206">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=400206#400206</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>The Overpowering Characters of Rei and Asuka</p>
</blockquote>
<p>‚Äî So big changes were being intended at Atami.</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> The truth is, the day before I went to Atami, I received a call from (Toshimichi) Otsuki-san, and I was told that they would leave the content alone, and there was only one matter they wanted to pursue. At that time, based on the current screenplay, the film was projected to run between 130 and 140 minutes, and the aim was to reduce it to less than 120.</p>
<p>‚Äî Besides yourself, who were the members of the retreat?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> There were the directors, Anno-san, Tsurumaki-san, and Masayuki-san, as well as (Ikki) Todoroki-san, who was performing secretarial duties.</p>
<p>‚Äî So you begin the Atami Retreat with the assumption that you would be deepening Mari‚Äôs character a little and fine-tuning the screenplay to reduce the length of the film, but what was the reality?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Concerning the matter of strengthening Mari‚Äôs character, Anno-san had already been asking me if I had any ideas, so I started to investigate the problem. However, as I worked through it, the twosome ‚ÄúRei and Asuka‚Äù was such a powerful combination that they seemed to stand in the way. When I tried to investigate what made this pair so strong, I realized that this combination followed the archetype of the so called ‚Äúharem anime‚Äù, and that all the desires, lusts, and dreams of young men were bound up in them.</p>
<p>One ‚Äútype‚Äù is the girl who was a childhood friend, who has always been with you since you were born, and with whom there are no new or strange feelings. Rei is established to resemble a ‚Äúmother‚Äù in some respects, and so she produces in young men a feeling of distance [from things?] as though they were still half in the womb.<a href="#fn33" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref33"><sup>33</sup></a> Now, Asuka‚Äôs particular type is that of the girl who comes from a foreign country. This also produces a very good feeling. Probably it is the male instinct to think, in some respects, that girls from another world are better than girls who are familiar and close to hand (laughs).</p>
<p>‚Äî Certainly, if we assume that there is a male instinct to ‚Äúspread‚Äù DNA, or propagate the species by mixing heterogeneous elements.</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> The sadness and happiness of young men is bound up in the fact that they always possess these two contradictory wishes. The so-called ‚ÄúHarem Anime‚Äù genre is for the most part intended to satisfy these desires. In ‚ÄúUrusei Yatsura‚Äù, Shinobu is the Japanese girl who was one‚Äôs childhood friend and always by one‚Äôs side, and Lum is the ‚Äúalien girl‚Äù. We say ‚Äúalien‚Äù, but [such characters] perhaps [have] an ‚ÄúAmerican‚Äù image. Rei and Asuka exactly fit the pattern of this ‚Äúperfect lineup‚Äù.</p>
<p>Now, coming up with a plan as regards the third girl who must compete with this ‚Äúultimate combination‚Äù seemed to me a very difficult job. In addition, Director Anno had not, up to this point, developed anything himself, but, expressing the desire for a completely new character, had left Mari‚Äôs development to others.</p>
<p>This being the case, my first proposal for an additional type was a Sapphire (from [Tezuka Osamu‚Äôs] <em>Princess Knight</em>) type. If Rei and Asuka are completely different types, I wondered if a ‚Äúneutral‚Äù, lighthearted type who battles with an ‚Äúinnocent‚Äù image would be good. At this point, though Anno-san agreed that it would be good, he thought a Wato (Chiyoko) type (from [Tezuka‚Äôs] <em>The Three-Eyed One</em>) would be more realistic, and he got quite excited about it.</p>
<p>However, Tsurumaki-san, who had been listening nearby, was looking at us with a distant expression. It looked as though he was thinking, ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs a pleasant conversation [for you], but just who is going to be saddled with the difficulty of placing that character in the world of Eva?‚Äù (laughs) I think the result of finalizing Mari‚Äôs appeal was that Tsurumaki-san was made to suffer with storyboards.</p>
<p>‚Äî Since viewers were heavily anticipating a new character from the first film‚Äôs preview, you want to give Mari more to do; was that the atmosphere [at Atami]?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> As we had many conversations relating to Mari, I think it was. As for other images, there was the part of a Miko-san [shrine maiden] channeling the gods. She is not ‚Äúpractical‚Äù like Asuka, but thinks about ‚Äúdeep‚Äù things, like someone who somehow can see mysterious things like those connected with the gods. She is not ‚Äúunworldly‚Äù to Rei‚Äôs extent and she talks a lot. As nothing had yet solidified, we had these sorts of discussions about ideas.</p>
<p>‚Äî I have a feeling that those ideas influenced the final film. What other discussions did you have about Mari?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> We didn‚Äôt just discuss her character traits, but we were also tangled up in discussing to what extent she should appear in the film. I remember that this caused everyone a great deal of distress. If we wanted to increase her appearances we could, but, because we were limited by the running time of the film, the number of scenes depicting the activity of other characters would be reduced. Even watching the completed film, there are selections we made at the last minute. If we added more Mari, we would have to further cut strong scenes involving Rei and Asuka, but if we didn‚Äôt, then there would have been no point to putting Mari in the second film [to begin with]. In the end I think we were impressed with her character and have high expectations for her in the future.</p>
<p>‚Äî In the original scenario Mari was the daughter of a distinguished English family who kept dogs and cats, and so on; what were the circumstances [relating to that]?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Speaking of that, I also remember conversations like, ‚ÄúWhat if we gave her tattoos of the names of all the pets she‚Äôs kept up until now?‚Äù For example, we would insert a bath scene where we see the area from her chest to her stomach is completely covered in tattoos. If she gets asked, ‚ÄúWhy do you have them?‚Äù she‚Äôd answer something like, ‚ÄúThey‚Äôre the names of all my pets that have died up until now. The tattoos ensure I don‚Äôt forget them, and that they still ‚Äòlive‚Äô with me‚Äù.</p>
<p>‚Äî That‚Äôs a striking character trait.</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Did this development survive or die off? Because Mari hasn‚Äôt undressed yet, nobody knows (laughs). With things like this, we tried too hard to develop Mari‚Äôs character traits; when I think back on it, we were only discussing ‚Äúforced‚Äù or ‚Äúabsurd‚Äù things. In asking ‚Äúhow can we beat Rei or Asuka?‚Äù we had a tendency to get a little bit too much into an ‚Äúimpact contest‚Äù.</p>
<p>‚Äî After all, if you want to insert Mari somewhere, you have to leave out Rei or Asuka. We also heard about this difficulty from Tsurumaki-san.</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> There were versions of the unfinished screenplay where Mari appears only at the beginning, and doesn‚Äôt participate in the battle at the end.</p>
</section>
<section id="part-3-1" class="level3">
<h3>Part 3</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=401642#401642">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=401642#401642</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Boarding ‚ÄòEva‚Äô Again After Sixteen Years</p>
</blockquote>
<p>‚Äî This memo<a href="#fn34" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref34"><sup>34</sup></a> you put out, with what kind of feeling was it made use of?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> That was mainly a list of scenes to be cut. At that time we were still wondering whether scenes like the pilots going to eat Ramen together should be left in. I not only participated in the original TV series but watched it as a fan, so I knew which scenes were my favorites. However, as far as the film was concerned, I thought it was best to focus on Shinji-kun‚Äôs scenes. In addition, I would comply with (the producer) Otsuki‚Äôs order to bring the film under 120 minutes. Therefore, I rapidly cut sequences which, although famous, did not have a strong relation to the main story. However, as I did this everyone naturally saw favorite scenes being cut, one by one, and because of this I was becoming increasingly shut out by the group (laughs). For example, Anno-san lost his favorite Misato scene‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚Äî Which Misato scene?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> There were many scenes at the start of the script showing a deeper friendship between Misato, Ritsuko, and Kaji that were discarded. They were ‚Äúfilm-like‚Äù scenes and, from the dramatic perspective, very good; however, because I thought it was best to organize the film around Shinji, I proposed that they be cut. Because Anno is the chief director, if he hates a cut he can prevent it by saying ‚ÄúI want that scene to stay‚Äù. However, he doesn‚Äôt do so. Nevertheless, when he‚Äôs displeased the atmosphere becomes very oppressive (laughs).</p>
<p>Furthermore, when even Tsurumaki-san, the one person I expected to support me, started saying things like ‚ÄúI‚Äôm an Asuka fan, and I won‚Äôt be happy if this scene gets cut‚Äù, I had a feeling like, ‚ÄúHuh?‚Äù (laughs). At that time, Masayuki-san came to my rescue, saying ‚ÄúLook, we should just do as Enokido-san says, okay?‚Äù I had the impression that I had just barely kept my place [at Atami] (laughs). Masayuki probably decided to bring ‚Äúbalance‚Äù to the sessions (laughs).</p>
<p>‚Äî It was difficult, wasn‚Äôt it? (laughs)</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Only, once we had cut a few scenes, naturally the next problem was the opposite one; owing to the cuts you could begin to see gaps detracting from the organization of the whole. As these gaps arose from cuts I had made, naturally I, as the person responsible, had to fix them. For example, while in the first half of the film Asuka appears as a character who strongly repels others, in the second half she becomes a little kinder, and develops into a character who is concerned with Shinji‚Äôs feelings. This development is crucial, but I had a feeling that, due to my excessive cuts, the basis for this change became too thin. Trying to make up for that loss, I had the idea for a scene where Asuka, unable to bear her loneliness, enters, uninvited, the room of the sleeping Shinji.<a href="#fn35" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref35"><sup>35</sup></a> The scene used in the film was translated from the concept almost exactly. By inserting this scene, it seemed likely that something of a connection between the ‚Äúfirst half‚Äù Asuka and the ‚Äúsecond half‚Äù Asuka could be skillfully established.</p>
<p>Because I had broken off my journey aboard the TV series in the middle of the voyage, this time I had the privilege of boarding the ‚ÄúNew Theatrical Edition‚Äù in the middle of the voyage, and I have the profound impression that Eva, [for me,] is finally connected by a single line. I had the privilege of a rare personal experience of which few other examples exist (smiles).</p>
<p>‚Äî There‚Äôs not many stories of people bridging a gap of ten years or more.</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Near the beginning of ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù, Asuka says: ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs not just the color that‚Äôs different. (‚Ä¶) This is the world‚Äôs first ‚Äòtrue‚Äô Evangelion, designed for real combat‚Äù. 16 years ago I wrote those lines of dialogue for episode eight of the television series. When I heard those lines spoken in the movie, I was so overcome with emotion I couldn‚Äôt speak. There were two sides to the feeling: ‚ÄúAt last, the line is connected‚Äù, and ‚ÄúThe journey isn‚Äôt over‚Äù (smiles). I have the impression that the train I departed from has returned as a high-speed express, and, just as before, I am a passenger once more (smiles).</p>
</section>
<section id="enokido-memos" class="level3">
<h3>Enokido memos</h3>
