<section id="kazuya-tsurumaki" class="level2">
<h2>Kazuya Tsurumaki</h2>
<section id="background-2" class="level3">
<h3>Background</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=408691#408691">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=408691#408691</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>‚ÄúThe CRC 2.0 Tsurumaki interview is actually, I believe, a revised and expanded version of an interview included in the original Eva 2.0 theatrical program, including material from an additional, later interview.‚Äù</p>
</blockquote>
</section>
<section id="part-1-2" class="level3">
<h3>Part 1</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=419178#419178">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=419178#419178</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>A major turning point following the ‚ÄòPrelude‚Äô premiere<a href="#fn36" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref36"><sup>36</sup></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>‚Äî To begin with, I‚Äôd like to speak with you for the program to be distributed before the premiere. According to Chief Director Anno‚Äôs intention, it was decided that we would ‚Äúpublish an interview with Makki entitled ‚Äòthe man who destroyed Eva.‚Äô‚Äù<a href="#fn37" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref37"><sup>37</sup></a> Before we begin, I‚Äôd first like to confirm that you were made aware of that intention.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> This seems suspicious (laughs). As far as making me into ‚Äúthe criminal responsible for destroying [Eva]‚Äù is concerned, I‚Äôll resist with all my might.</p>
<p>‚Äî Only, if we look at ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù as a destroyed Eva, surely everyone would want to know the details of how and why this happened.<a href="#fn38" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref38"><sup>38</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> As far as [the title] ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù is concerned, Anno-san probably discovered a new reason for it part of the way through. As usual. Although, I think it would have been better if Anno-san had taken the lead in destroying [Eva] himself. [It would surely have been difficult for him to destroy it. I think he well understood that, and had no choice [but to do as he did].<a href="#fn39" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref39"><sup>39</sup></a>] However, it was not myself alone who destroyed Eva. Even Masayuki-san, or Sadamoto-san, who writes the manga, would have been fine [for the interview].</p>
<p>‚Äî This successful ‚Äúdestruction‚Äù was unexpectedly the core [of the film]. So [the conception of] a ‚Äújo - ha - kyuu‚Äù [Â∫èÁ†¥ÊÄ•] structure where you would begin destroying Eva in the second part was not present from the beginning?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> In the initial stages we thought more in terms of a recap or summary film; we didn‚Äôt think that we would ‚Äúbreak‚Äù [anything]. We decided upon the subtitles ‚Äújo - ha - kyuu‚Äù themselves relatively early on. They only had the meaning ‚Äú1, 2, 3‚Äù - at the time I didn‚Äôt think that ‚Äúha‚Äù [‚ÄúBreak‚Äù] had any special significance. The development of the story of ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù was already underway before we started work on ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù.<a href="#fn40" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref40"><sup>40</sup></a></p>
<p>‚Äî I have the impression that the development of ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù and ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù began at the same time.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Right. We decided, with relatively few objections, that we would bring ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù to a climax with episode six of the TV series, and immediately after that we began developing the story of ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù. However, work on ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù became increasingly hectic, so we decided to just focus on making ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù first. We returned to ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù once we had just about finished ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù.</p>
<p>‚Äî For my part, I was reading through the script for ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù around the time ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù was completed (the latter part of August 2007). Also, (Shinji) Higuchi-san was supposed to have drawn the storyboards for ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù that summer. At this point, the contents [of the film] are probably quite different [than they were, at that point].</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> It would turn out that more than just the plot would be developed further. In any case, after the premiere of ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù, Anno-san proposed that we include more of the new character, Mari, and it was decided that we would revisit the script. My impression was that ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù was received more favorably than expected; furthermore, the preview for the next film was very well received. So, I think Anno-san probably thought, ‚ÄúI want to give the viewers more service‚Äù. Probably, [his] specific means [of doing that] was to place Mari more prominently [in the film].</p>
<p>‚Äî Considering Anno‚Äôs ‚Äúspirit of service‚Äù, that would naturally be the case, right? So, that would lead to [Anno] increasing the number of Mari‚Äôs appearances?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> The truth is, at the earliest stage of planning, Mari was such a character that, in the extreme case, if she hadn‚Äôt spoken at all, it would have been okay. For example, Misato just reading the materials on her, [and saying] ‚ÄúIt seems that Unit-05 was in Hong Kong and had a battle with an angel. The pilot was this person‚Äù - would have been fine, I think‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚Äî In that case, she would become an amazingly weak character.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Yeah. The appearance of a new character and Eva Unit-05 was requested by executive producer (Toshimichi) Otsuki-san. I think the motive was a commercial one - to strengthen the appeal of the film.<a href="#fn41" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref41"><sup>41</sup></a></p>
<p>‚Äî Surely, the new films themselves become a burden to the extent they represent a story that preexists the new character; you had to ‚Äúcreate carefully‚Äù, right?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> [Yes,] because at first we intended [simply] to summarize the original series. For example, the current structure in which the new character is actively involved before the main titles was put in place at that stage in the film‚Äôs plot [development]. In addition, [she] would appear only once more, watching the battle just before the climax. That was the extent to which she appeared.</p>
<p>‚Äî So, she was hardly related to the characters of the original story.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> It‚Äôs Anno-san‚Äôs usual method. He allows possibilities to remain without making up his mind. By no means have things been decided. Because, if he was bound to a decision, he wouldn‚Äôt be able to do anything but that. He was still undecided about how to handle her, and at that time he probably thought that introducing her but leaving her without definite relations [to anything] would be safe for the moment.</p>
<p>‚Äî I see. In a different set of circumstances,<a href="#fn42" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref42"><sup>42</sup></a> I would also have thought, ‚ÄúAs expected, the storyline of Eva is quite fixed, and new interventions are not possible‚Äù.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Naturally. Therefore, daring to have her appear at the core of the story, even more, bringing her close to the center of the drama - in short, we intended to make her a character who would change the story. That was the major shift following the premiere of ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù.</p>
</section>
<section id="part-2-2" class="level3">
<h3>Part 2</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>What occurred with the increase of Mari‚Äôs scenes<a href="#fn43" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref43"><sup>43</sup></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>‚Äî The result being that [the story] would become increasingly different from the script that you had prepared?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> We were almost starting everything over again. We had hardly thought about what would be changed, and how it would be changed, in order to incorporate Mari. It was from that point, I think, that we really began.</p>
<p>‚Äî So, the question of how to destroy Eva ends up really being the question of how to connect Mari [to the existing story].</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Right. However, while we had resolved to change [the story], Anno-san had for one reason or another not thought at all about the elements of Mari‚Äôs character. As a result, I was continually requesting explanations in regard to them. When I requested an explanation of Mari‚Äôs character before we began doing the storyboards for the pre-title sequence, Anno-san gave me a rather abstract, ‚Äúthematic‚Äù explanation.</p>
<p>‚Äî ‚ÄúThematic?‚Äù</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> It was, ‚ÄúBy introducing Mari, we will destroy the world of Eva‚Äù. Concerning this idea of Mari as a character who represents the subtitle ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù, the explanation that we would directly project her ‚Äúthematic‚Äù character traits onto the story was not sufficient, so I just smiled and nodded. However, we were about to draw the storyboards without something essential - Mari‚Äôs concrete character was undetermined. The resulting stress would continue for a long time [after that].</p>
<p>‚Äî The establishment of her character - in other words, her personality?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Is she a girl with a calm demeanor, or a girl with an intense personality, or a <em>dojikko</em> [clumsy girl]? Even that much wasn‚Äôt clear. I felt like it changed each time the script was revised. Even if the theme of her character was ‚Äúthe destruction of Eva‚Äôs story‚Äù, there were numerous concrete ways you could conceive of doing that. In the extreme case, she could ‚Äústeal‚Äù Shinji and destroy all his relationships up to that point, or act as a ‚Äúnonsense‚Äù character who would destroy the ‚Äúserious‚Äù worldview [of Eva]. As there was no trace of a [fixed] methodology according to which she would destroy [Eva], the arguments concerning her continued endlessly.</p>
<p>‚Äî Which parts did the arguments center upon?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Certainly Mari‚Äôs appearances had increased. Furthermore, if there were scenes where Mari appeared by herself, that was still fine. Even in the early stages of the plot[‚Äôs development], we didn‚Äôt really feel that such scenes were a problem. The difficulty lay in her relationships with other characters. Especially, if we intended to portray a relationship between Shinji and Mari, it would entail strange things happening. At one point she would have Rei Ayanami‚Äôs role in relation to Shinji, at another point Asuka‚Äôs, at another point Misato‚Äôs. There was a sense that her character was changing depending upon the circumstances of each scene. In the first place, if it‚Äôs Rei‚Äôs role, Rei herself can do it, and if it‚Äôs Asuka‚Äôs role, Asuka herself can do it. To the extent that this newly arrived character, Mari, is just partially substituting for roles that other people have carried out up until now, the story itself is really unchanged. My impression was, if that‚Äôs going to be the case, Mari is probably not needed.</p>
<p>Because a new character is introduced, naturally, it‚Äôs already become a different story, but if we step back and look at it, almost nothing has changed. That‚Äôs useless. As a result, on one occasion Anno-san handed off this problem to [Y≈çji] Enokido-san. Basically, he told [Enokido] that he wanted to create a plot in which Mari‚Äôs character was more developed. It‚Äôs not a brief story; I remember thinking that it was quite a serious situation. For my part, because I thought the fact that Anno-san was writing the scripts himself<a href="#fn44" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref44"><sup>44</sup></a> was an important characteristic of the new films, it [seemed] all the more [serious]. Partially because of that, Enokido-san‚Äôs position, it seemed, was that he would absolutely not submit plots or scripts, but [only] ideas. What came out of this was an extremely eccentric, interesting, Enokido-like idea. In short, [Enokido] proactively made use of the fact that Mari could not simply act as a substitute.</p>
<p>‚Äî In specific terms, how did [Enokido] intend [Mari] to act?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> To put it simply, it was an idea where Mari completely usurped Asuka‚Äôs role. For example, Asuka is unable to pilot Unit-02, because Mari is constantly getting to things before Asuka. Mari even thrusts herself into the middle of the relationship between Shinji and Asuka; [Asuka is] completely thwarted. Even though Asuka makes a great effort to fulfill the role she played at the time of the TV series, because Mari is always there it becomes impossible for her to do it; something like that.</p>
<p>‚Äî That‚Äôs interesting.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> The reaction of Asuka fans to it would probably be terrifying (laughs). Because, in Enokido‚Äôs idea, Asuka, thwarted by Mari, is never able to pilot Unit-02. There were voices on the staff pointing out the size of the risk [involved], but Anno-san somehow understood [the idea], saying, ‚ÄúWell, I‚Äôm going to take that idea and put it in the script‚Äù. However‚Ä¶ [this idea] immediately went back to the drawing board (laughs).<a href="#fn45" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref45"><sup>45</sup></a> For example, when Asuka tries to pilot Unit-02 at the time of the battle with the eighth angel, she is told by Ritsuko, ‚ÄúMari, the pilot who arrived on short notice from Europe, can pilot Unit-02, so you are on standby‚Äù. Asuka is mortified. That was Enokido‚Äôs idea, but in Anno-san‚Äôs script, he changed it so that the two of them would be piloting Unit-02 together (laughs).</p>
<p>‚Äî ‚Äú<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ninin-Baori" title="Wikipedia: Ninin-Baori">Ninin-Baori</a>‚Äù (laughs)?<a href="#fn46" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref46"><sup>46</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> It‚Äôs excusable to just focus on the good things, but [Anno] was trying so hard to please everybody that the story was becoming confusing. Probably Anno-san thought that the story would not change unless he could deeply connect Mari to it, and for this reason he tried to place all the responsibility for changing the story upon Mari. Nevertheless, contrary to his intentions, even though he had tried to introduce Mari, he was not able to change the story.</p>
<p>‚Äî It‚Äôs as though some mysterious, compelling force was operating.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> But, I somehow understand that everyone experiences this. We don‚Äôt change [so easily], even though we swear, ‚Äústarting tomorrow, I will change!‚Äù (laughs) Being unable [to change] despite knowing [you should]; that‚Äôs something common to everyone. I think, in due time, Anno-san will reveal the real reason [for its existence] himself, but when Masayuki-san first did the storyboards for the battle with the eighth angel, the scene where the two pilot together was storyboarded, based upon the plot [at that time].</p>
<p>‚Äî How [did Anno] get them both onto [the Eva]?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> It‚Äôs as though Asuka secretly got on ahead of time (laughs). It wasn‚Äôt just there, [though]. Things like that continued to happen almost entirely throughout. So, we were truly in difficulty. [Anno] said there would be changes in ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù, and in practice more than 90% [of the film] was [comprised of] new scenes, but, even though we had taken the trouble to produce this new material, the story had not changed. Of course the situations, the characters, and the dialogue had changed. However, if we examine the significance of what was done there, we will get something like, ‚ÄúEh? This happened in episode xx‚Äù, or ‚ÄúThis scene [could go] in episode xx‚Äù.</p>
<p>‚Äî Hmm‚Ä¶ It‚Äôs as though you repainted [Eva], but the sense or significance of the TV series rose to the surface from the foundation.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> So, it was coming to seem like a summary version made with some slightly new material. A while ago, I had been told that the ‚ÄúEvangelion‚Äù TV series was quite rigidly fixed; it was, I think, certainly like that.<a href="#fn47" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref47"><sup>47</sup></a> It seemed like, if you change things in one place, things go badly not only there but elsewhere as well; a host of derivative problems arise. If you try to fix it, it‚Äôs an enormous task to make the story consistent everywhere.<a href="#fn48" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref48"><sup>48</sup></a></p>
<p>‚Äî Even if it goes well, won‚Äôt the ‚Äúspirit‚Äù of the original series still end up dwelling there?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Yes. This sort of thing continued, and for a while we were truly in difficulties. I think that was the main reason the script couldn‚Äôt be fixed, and that as a result [we] spent so much time doing storyboards.</p>
<p>‚Äî Even though they were deliberated to the point of staging a retreat for the script, there were some things that just couldn‚Äôt be ‚Äúboiled down‚Äù, right?<a href="#fn49" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref49"><sup>49</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Well, I think the Atami Retreat, which Enokido-san participated in, was extremely worthwhile. An audacious idea for the last scene, which was almost all right [as presented], emerged there. That was the development, which remains now, whereby Shinji rescues Rei. As far as the film‚Äôs climax goes, the work to be done after that hardly concerned us. The difficulty was arranging for Mari‚Äôs involvement, [which was necessary] in order to bring the story to that point. The most simple solution was - just as in the early stages of the story - to keep Mari‚Äôs appearances to a minimum, to leave her with no relationship with Shinji or Asuka, and for [the story] to follow a course similar to the TV series. In the end, this [approach] would go the most smoothly.<a href="#fn50" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref50"><sup>50</sup></a></p>
<p>‚Äî A course leading up to episode 19 of the television series.<a href="#fn51" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref51"><sup>51</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Yes. Strictly speaking, the part corresponding to episode 19 incorporates parts [of the series] from up to episode 23. Rei self-destructs in the TV series; [here] Shinji rescues her, and she is not made to self-destruct. Keeping things the same besides that was the safest way to do it. However, Mari had appeared [in the story], so she somehow had to act; we had to leave a path open for Mari. That was the most stressful [part].</p>
</section>
<section id="part-4-1" class="level3">
<h3>Part 4</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=408691#408691">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=408691#408691</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>[Incorporating] change itself into the structure of the film</p>
</blockquote>
<p>‚Äî Setting Mari aside, having Asuka pilot Unit-03 was a major change in ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù. How was this decision made?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Just as with Mari, we wanted Asuka to be significantly involved in the story. Since we decided to make the new films we‚Äôve somehow felt misgivings [about Asuka?]. When we [developed] the plot there were many scenes and dialogues involving Asuka, but we weren‚Äôt able to assign her a role in the story. She didn‚Äôt decisively impact Shinji, Rei, or the others. To say it plainly, we had the feeling that she was becoming something like a character who only ‚Äúmade noise‚Äù at the side. Asuka is a crucial character, so we wanted to involve her more in the story. She‚Äôs a popular character, so we hated the idea of her appearing as ‚Äúside entertainment‚Äù.</p>
<p>‚Äî So how did she become linked with the Unit-03 sequence?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Sadamoto-san‚Äôs advice was important. There was an initial conversation where he made the point that, ‚Äúamong Kaworu, Touji, and Asuka, you will not be able to sufficiently develop more than two of them, probably only one‚Äù. Because he had carefully considered his experiences putting together the manga, I placed great weight on his opinion.</p>
<p>‚Äî In actuality, the story of Touji and Unit-03 remained in the manga version, right?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Yeah. With a manga, in a way, you have a great deal of freedom. For example, you could use an entire volume of the manga just for Episode 18 of the TV series, and it should be okay. I myself really liked Touji‚Äôs episode; I think it was good in that it broadened the scope of the series, and so I understand Sadamoto-san closely following the TV version in his manga. However, because a film has to develop a ‚Äúflow‚Äù within a limited amount of time, we wouldn‚Äôt have the space to closely develop three characters in ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù. I could predict that, when we positioned the TV series‚Äô Unit-03 incident as a crucial, climactic episode, we would have no choice but to abandon portraying Asuka [as a major character]. If that happened Asuka‚Äôs role in the plot would completely vanish. Moreover, after the Unit-03 incident, even the scenes where she does appear were bound to be reduced. If this is the case, could we simply replace Touji with Asuka? I tried proposing this to Anno-san, including Sadamoto-san‚Äôs views on the matter.</p>
<p>‚Äî It seems that, for the film, a great deal depended on this determination. So this plan was accepted with no objections?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> No, there was considerable resistance from the staff. I think it‚Äôs only natural. I myself was afraid of making such a change. Anno-san, as well, probably wasn‚Äôt eager to do it at first. Nevertheless, the decision about the Unit-03 incident had to be made at an early stage.</p>
<p>‚Äî I think the result of the plan to have Asuka pilot Unit-03 was a point where the new film impacts [the audience] with an impression of its character. I wondered if it was like a symbolic proclamation: ‚ÄúWe are making something different‚Äù.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> When we began the new films, I wondered if we could actually create a film about the condition of ‚Äúremaking‚Äù a work. Something like [what happened with] <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apocalypse%20Now" title="Wikipedia: Apocalypse Now">Apocalypse Now</a></em>. Filming in a jungle far from their home country, [hearing] a language they didn‚Äôt understand, [following] a schedule with no end in sight, lacking sufficient funding; the very circumstances of a film crew making a movie about Vietnam strongly ‚Äúsynchronized‚Äù not only with the mental state of the soldiers who fought in Vietnam but with an America unable to withdraw from a war that had become a ‚Äúquagmire‚Äù.</p>
<p>So, I wondered if it was possible to develop something like ‚Äúa film about the act itself of remaking the same thing over again‚Äù. It seems like ‚Ä¶ changes in the story would be stressful for the creators, to begin with, but also stressful for the characters in the film and for the viewing audience. I wondered if it was possible to make a film that took all of this into account.</p>
<p>‚Äî This ‚Äúmetafictional‚Äù approach is really interesting. It‚Äôs like a kind of ‚Äústress contest‚Äù between the creators and the viewers.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> So, when I asked Anno-san ‚ÄúHow would this be?‚Äù he immediately replied ‚ÄúNo. That‚Äôs useless‚Äù. (laughs) It‚Äôs certainly a different direction than the ‚Äúeasy-to-understand entertainment‚Äù which we initially aimed at with the new films. So, at that time I just gave it up. Nevertheless, during the course of its creation ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù certainly became like this‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚Äî I felt like the various changes within the story came off as things that you had aimed at from the beginning. No doubt about it.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Despite people saying ‚Äú<em>Kaeru Kaeru</em>‚Äù, [‚Äúchange, change‚Äù] in reality things stay the same as before and cannot be changed. It‚Äôs the same with the viewers, who, on the one hand, come to the theater anticipating changes, and, on the other hand, are prepared in advance to complain if the direction of the changes doesn‚Äôt suit them. This sender/receiver relationship exists naturally. Obviously, it‚Äôs something that‚Äôs both ‚Äúinside‚Äù and ‚Äúoutside‚Äù the film, between the ‚Äústory‚Äù and the ‚Äúreal world‚Äù. [When we speak of] ‚Äúfilm‚Äù [the word] also includes this [situation].<a href="#fn52" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref52"><sup>52</sup></a> As I wanted to aim for this at the start, I‚Äôm satisfied with the current state of the film, which I think is approaching that once- rejected and abandoned ‚Äúmetafictionality‚Äù.</p>
<p>‚Äî It‚Äôs a situation where there is a structural entanglement between something like reality and the creative situation or between something like the ‚Äúfilm‚Äù and the ‚Äúfan‚Äù.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> It‚Äôs certainly ‚ÄúEva-esque‚Äù.</p>
<p>‚Äî This is an amazingly thought-provoking account, in that it sheds light on what it means to transform Eva into ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù / to ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù Eva.<a href="#fn53" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref53"><sup>53</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> I don‚Äôt know to what extent the audience will be really interested in it! (laughs)</p>
<p>‚Äî No, no, it‚Äôs extraordinarily interesting. I think it‚Äôs a valuable account.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Certainly this should be an interesting conversation for the ‚Äúheavy‚Äù Eva fan. I myself also really like it. ‚ÄúTo repeat‚Äù, ‚Äúto remake‚Äù, ‚Äúto want to change‚Äù, ‚Äúto have to change;‚Äù these things themselves become the themes of the story, and produce a new structure. There is the TV series, and there are the new movies; a reiteration. ‚ÄúTo do it one more time‚Äù: within this development, one says one wants to change but does not. It‚Äôs as though one wants to change and yet one doesn‚Äôt want to change‚Ä¶ this incredible structure developed, and I really like it.</p>
</section>
<section id="part-5-1" class="level3">
<h3>Part 5</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>The magic that was hidden in Episode 19<a href="#fn54" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref54"><sup>54</sup></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>‚Äî Even though it‚Äôs interesting, the actual work must naturally have been difficult.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> There are different considerations if you are part of the creative process! (laughs) If you have control of this ‚Äúmeta‚Äù way of creating [something], then things aren‚Äôt too bad. At first I tried to exercise this control, but when I talked to Anno [I learned that] it was ‚Äúuseless‚Äù, so I thought, well, there‚Äôs nothing I can do. However, in this state where I had no control, [the film] became [‚Äúmetafictional‚Äù] in the end. That‚Äôs what happened.</p>
<p>‚Äî So it took care of itself?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Yes. It‚Äôs exactly a state where it‚Äôs been left to take care of itself. (laughs) I think that‚Äôs probably terrible, right?</p>
<p>‚Äî I‚Äôm sorry, but I think ‚Äúdeep‚Äù [ÊøÉ„ÅÑ] fans of Eva will absolutely say ‚Äúthat‚Äôs okay!‚Äù (laughs) Their fear and mistrust of a ‚Äúdestination unknown‚Äù melts away, owing to their ‚Äúpre-established harmony‚Äù [with the creators/franchise]. Moreover, if we watch the completed film, there‚Äôs no sign of things that were produced by ‚Äúgiving up control‚Äù. It‚Äôs beyond the imagination of anyone to sense what you were able to bring about and what formed [accidentally]. Moreover, it seems as though everything was calculated from the beginning‚Ä¶ I think that, certainly, is ‚ÄúEva-esque‚Äù, and an extremely interesting phenomenon.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> That‚Äôs true, isn‚Äôt it? Some time ago there was a topic of conversation dealing with the story structure of the TV series as being extremely fixed, extremely strong, and at the time I thought this way as well. I thought, ‚ÄúAnno-san, he‚Äôs amazing!‚Äù Amazing to come up with this structure. It‚Äôs a structure where turning over one piece brings the entire series of connections to life.<a href="#fn55" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref55"><sup>55</sup></a> I thought it was amazing. However, when I started to work on ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù, and we looked at and analyzed the climactic scene, corresponding to episode 19 of the series, over and over again, then I came to realize that this was not entirely true. Everybody really loves episode 19, and it‚Äôs said to be extremely well made, right?</p>
<p>‚Äî Yeah. In that [episode] we get a tightly compressed reiteration of the TV series up to that point; it‚Äôs a technique that shows us a condensed version of the story of Shinji‚Äôs growth, right?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Nevertheless, if you analyze the incredible ‚Äúmagic‚Äù happening there you will really understand. I don‚Äôt mean to be impolite, but, to put it simply, everybody is being deceived. Even we, the staff, were deceived.<a href="#fn56" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref56"><sup>56</sup></a></p>
<p>‚Äî What on earth do you mean by that?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> The most important point is that Shinji says there that he won‚Äôt pilot the Eva again. When Shinji decides to leave Tokyo-3, one moment he is separating from Misato at Hakone-Yumoto station, and before we know it he is in an underground shelter in the Geofront. When the Angel attacks he is standing on a hill overlooking Tokyo-3 - which lies on the other side of a mountain from Hakone-Yumoto<a href="#fn57" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref57"><sup>57</sup></a> - saying to himself ‚ÄúI won‚Äôt pilot‚Äù. But in the next scene he is in the underground shelter. While he is saying ‚ÄúI won‚Äôt pilot‚Äù his body is gradually coming closer and closer to Unit-01. I didn‚Äôt really realize this at the time. This also has to do with Masayuki‚Äôs transcendental editing technique and the fact that ‚ÄúBANK‚Äù is frequently used.<a href="#fn58" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref58"><sup>58</sup></a></p>
<p>‚Äî „Å™„Çì„Å†„ÅãË¶ãË¶ö„Åà„ÅÆ„Ç∑„Éº„É≥„Çí„Éë„ÉÉ„Éë„ÉÉ„Å®Áü≠„Åè„Å§„Å™„ÅÑ„Åß ÂÖ•„ÇåÂ≠ê„Å´„Åó„Å¶„ÅÇ„Çã„Åã„Çâ„ÄÅ„Çà„Åë„ÅÑÂç∞Ë±°„ÅåÂº∑„Åè„Å™„Å£„Å¶Ë¶ã„Åà„Çã„Çì„Åß„Åô„Çà„ÅÜ„Å≠„ÄÇ<a href="#fn59" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref59"><sup>59</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> In addition, there is also the lack of information characteristic of TV Anime. For example, there is the sky in the background behind the character, but no information is given outside of that; is he on the top of a mountain? Is he inside the city? We don‚Äôt really know.<a href="#fn60" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref60"><sup>60</sup></a> We are gradually disoriented by means of an accumulation of indeterminacies.</p>
<p>‚Äî Certainly, owing to the ‚Äúmagic‚Äù of the television image, we have the impression that, even though Shinji is going [somewhere] with all his might, we don‚Äôt know where he is.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> But if we observe carefully, we feel confused. Even at that [earlier] time I realized that much. My interpretation was that, even though Shinji was saying he wouldn‚Äôt pilot, he also understood that he had to pilot. As for his saying ‚ÄúI won‚Äôt pilot‚Äù, I believed that if he wasn‚Äôt saying it he would certainly pilot.<a href="#fn61" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref61"><sup>61</sup></a> As a result, although he was saying ‚ÄúI won‚Äôt pilot, I won‚Äôt pilot‚Äù, his body was going towards the center of the battle. Even though he came as far the Geofront, where the battle was raging, he was still saying ‚ÄúI won‚Äôt pilot, I won‚Äôt pilot‚Äù. Then Unit-02‚Äôs head falls down, and Unit-00 is damaged, and so on; and when [Shinji] goes outside Kaji is there, and they have a famous conversation. Finally, Shinji gives up and pilots, deciding that, ‚Äúas I thought, I have to pilot‚Ä¶ I knew it, but it was just as I expected‚Äù. That sort of development was how I interpreted things.</p>
<p>‚Äî That‚Äôs also my interpretation, and, I think, the interpretation of countless viewers‚Ä¶</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> [There must be a] ‚Äúhowever‚Äù, right? When I was doing the storyboards for ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù, and went to confirm with Anno-san that portraying Shinji like this was good, I was emphatically told, ‚ÄúWhat are you talking about, Makki? This is completely wrong!‚Äù What a shock I received! (laughs) Anno-san continues, ‚ÄúShinji really doesn‚Äôt want to pilot, and that‚Äôs what he says‚Äù. From my point of view Shinji‚Äôs declaration ‚ÄúI won‚Äôt pilot‚Äù was half a hate campaign against his father, a child and ‚Äúda-da‚Äù type situation. It was the same as a child who had quarreled with his father saying ‚ÄúIf that‚Äôs the case, I won‚Äôt study!‚Äù Emotionally, Shinji doesn‚Äôt want to pilot, but he understands that he has to. To that extent I had thought he was a ‚Äúgrown-up‚Äù character.</p>
<p>However, when I seriously thought over what Anno-san had said, I understood that Anno-san‚Äôs Shinji is not like that. I understood that he was a character who, if he feels he doesn‚Äôt want to pilot, absolutely will not pilot. Shinji is the exact opposite of what the conventional impression of him is. He is not cowardly and indecisive; he is obstinate and doesn‚Äôt pay any mind to other people.</p>
<p>‚Äî In short, a character who will not pilot, no matter what?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Exactly right. According to Anno-san, ‚ÄúHe pilots because he wants to pilot, and as long as he doesn‚Äôt want to pilot he won‚Äôt pilot‚Äù. But I remained unsatisfied. ‚ÄúThat would be acceptable if this were a trivial argument over something like studying.<a href="#fn62" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref62"><sup>62</sup></a> However, if he doesn‚Äôt pilot Eva, humanity will be destroyed, Misato will be in great difficulties, Rei Ayanami will have to undertake a suicide attack, and so on; even if he knows this, will he still not pilot Eva?‚Äù When I again tried to ask Anno-san this, he replied, ‚ÄúBecause Shinji is extremely angry there, his heart is closed and he doesn‚Äôt notice those things‚Äù.</p>
<p>When I was told that, I understood the irrational speech and conduct that could be sometimes seen in Anno-san! (laughs) In short, he‚Äôs someone who, once he starts to say he doesn‚Äôt like something, absolutely will not budge. From my perspective, at such times Anno-san is obstinate to what feels like an abnormal extent.</p>
<p>I am the opposite. I truthfully dislike even doing this interview for the program.<a href="#fn63" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref63"><sup>63</sup></a> However, since Anno-san wouldn‚Äôt do it, it seemed like someone had to‚Ä¶ I don‚Äôt care one way or the other about the interview.<a href="#fn64" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref64"><sup>64</sup></a> (laughs) But Anno-san, he‚Äôs someone who sometimes displays an irrational obstinacy reminiscent of Shinji in Episode 19.</p>
<p>All of this is just a guess,<a href="#fn65" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref65"><sup>65</sup></a> but Anno-san has never in his life had the experience ‚ÄúI didn‚Äôt want to do it, but I did it‚Äù. If he did something, it was only because he had wanted to do it. For myself, there were many things I did because I wanted to do them, but just about as many things I didn‚Äôt want to do, but did because I had no choice.</p>
<p>‚Äî It‚Äôs generally the same for every working adult, right?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> However, was Shinji really portrayed in episode 19 the way Anno-san said he was? No matter what, the question was there, but when I ask Masayuki-san, who was responsible for directing that episode, for confirmation, for one reason or another he doesn‚Äôt give me a clear answer. As a result I wonder if he is changing the depiction of Shinji‚Äôs character behind Anno-san‚Äôs back.<a href="#fn66" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref66"><sup>66</sup></a></p>
<p>‚Äî Isn‚Äôt that an even more shocking discovery?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> A reason that can explain why Shinji returned to the Geofront‚Ä¶ In short, in his heart Shinji believes that he has to pilot Eva so he goes of his own volition. Even if the truth is that Anno-san‚Äôs script arrives at a different explanation, [the other] is easily inserted. If such things as Shinji‚Äôs monologue alongside the voices of the evacuees, the stream of announcements on the public address system, and so on, are present, Anno-san will believe that ‚Äúthis is certainly following my script‚Äù. However, Masayuki-san treats that skillfully, and then inserts an ambiguous depiction which could be taken a different way. As far as this is the case, Masayuki-san‚Äôs directoral plan should have been fundamentally the same as my interpretation.</p>
<p>‚Äî I‚Äôve got it. It‚Äôs that ambiguity that is the main reason viewers have such sympathetic feelings for episode 19.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Right. To the extent they hold those feelings, Shinji is not obstinate. The impressions [produced by the episode] can be interpreted this way.<a href="#fn67" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref67"><sup>67</sup></a> I think Masayuki-san‚Äôs words were something like, ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs this because that stupid Anno said so, but‚Ä¶‚Äù<a href="#fn68" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref68"><sup>68</sup></a> (laughs) I wondered if [Masayuki-san], like myself, wanted to avoid a definite conflict or rejection, and so, with a skillful deception, had things both ways. ???<a href="#fn69" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref69"><sup>69</sup></a> However, Masayuki-san‚Äôs unique editing technique and film-like montages [Êò†ÁîªÁöÑ„Å™„É¢„É≥„Çø„Éº„Ç∏„É•] were accompanied by the lack of information peculiar to television; [the result is] something established through a perfect balance.</p>
<p>‚Äî This is a very interesting explanation. As a result, what the viewers finally see is left to the imagination of the viewers. So the viewers will reach the conclusion ‚ÄúI was able to see what I wanted to see‚Äù.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Right. Precisely because the information provided in TV anime is slight, it‚Äôs left up to the viewers. The technique depends upon this precondition. However, if we attempted to do the same thing with film-quality images, then that would absolutely lead to problems. I believed we couldn‚Äôt achieve the same thing [in the film] using the technique from episode 19.</p>
</section>
<section id="part-6-1" class="level3">
<h3>Part 6</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/post/409304/Evangelion-20-CRC-Tsurumaki-Interview/#409304">http://forum.evageeks.org/post/409304/Evangelion-20-CRC-Tsurumaki-Interview/#409304</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>What is it that strengthens the structure of Eva?<a href="#fn70" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref70"><sup>70</sup></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>‚Äî Even if episode 19 is a masterpiece, in reality its structure lacks strength. Notwithstanding that, why does Eva as a whole appear this way [i.e., to be structurally sound]?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> From this point on, these are completely my own suppositions, so Anno-san would probably reject this, but the secret is, I think, likely to be Anno-san himself. Anno-san is not someone who creates according to an inductive method<a href="#fn71" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref71"><sup>71</sup></a>, but according to a deductive method<a href="#fn72" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref72"><sup>72</sup></a>. The inductive methodology would involve deciding one one‚Äôs destination and working out what you will do to get there, but that‚Äôs not the case [with Anno], who hasn‚Äôt really decided what the end point will be. Even if he has decided [on something, he‚Äôs done it] very vaguely, and as he tries to go on he gets bored with it.<a href="#fn73" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref73"><sup>73</sup></a> I have reached the point where I firmly believe this.</p>
<p>To put it another way, he just ends up choosing the things he likes. For example, suppose that there is a fork in the road. [He‚Äôs?] faced with [the choice] ‚Äúsave Rei/not save Rei‚Äù and [he] chooses ‚Äúsave Rei‚Äù. [He‚Äôs] faced with [the choice] ‚Äúpilot Eva/not pilot Eva‚Äù and [he] chooses ‚Äúpilot Eva‚Äù. [He] goes on choosing the path he likes from a continuous series of two alternatives. The structure of Eva‚Äôs story is assembled in this manner. It‚Äôs no longer a structure.</p>
<p>‚Äî It‚Äôs just like a single road, right? If this is the case, the story of ‚ÄúEva‚Äù as a whole is Anno Hideaki‚Äôs ‚Äúindividuality‚Äù<a href="#fn74" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref74"><sup>74</sup></a> itself. Isn‚Äôt it like what he told me, somewhere in the past: ‚Äú_mata modotte shimau‚Äú?<a href="#fn75" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref75"><sup>75</sup></a></p>
<p>TODO: who said this following line, the interviewer or Tsurumaki?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Because I had a different impression at the time of the first CRC interview with Chief Director Hideaki Anno, I am digging deeper using what I heard. ???<a href="#fn76" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref76"><sup>76</sup></a> [Anno said that] one of his objectives for the ‚ÄúNew Movie Edition‚Äù was to reconstruct Evangelion as an ‚Äúentertainment‚Äù liberated from his own ‚Äúauthority‚Äù [or ‚Äúauthorial nature‚Äù: ‰ΩúÂÆ∂ÊÄß], so that even other directors would be able to create [future ‚ÄúEva‚Äù works]. In reality, ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù, despite imparting a sense of this potentiality ‚Ä¶ This was the meaning of the phrase.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> However, in the end, I can‚Äôt understand it any further. Because the fact is that the structure of the story appears to be solid, and Anno-san is someone who won‚Äôt change his mind once he‚Äôs decided.</p>
<p>‚Äî Is the foundation of this solidity then Hideaki Anno‚Äôs ‚Äúindividuality‚Äù?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Let‚Äôs say we had an Artificial Intelligence which, where there are two choices, is unfailingly biased towards selecting what is, even if only by a small margin, ‚Äúthe bright side‚Äù. So if we have, say, the numerical values ‚Äú49‚Äù and ‚Äú51‚Äù, it will certainly choose ‚Äú51‚Äù. The AI‚Äôs route is consistent. There is no necessity or reason to go off course. In this sort of manner, I believe all of Eva‚Äôs options were selected by Anno-san according to his liking. The reality is, now, ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù has also become like this. (laughs) Even though I think Anno-san wants to change, I think there are certainly also reasons why he was simply unable to change. Even at the time of the TV series, everything was already [just] Anno-san selecting the direction he liked. ‚ÄúIf we do this, it will be kakkouii‚Äù. ‚ÄúI like this direction.‚Äù ‚ÄúIt will be fun if this happens.‚Äù Because he always chose such a way, changing that means having to do things he dislikes. So, he wasn‚Äôt able to change‚Ä¶ That‚Äôs how I understood things.</p>
<p>‚Äî I see. Interesting. My ease in understanding this conversation is due to my memory of a symbolic remark made by a certain person at the time when ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù was first being advertised. ‚ÄúOf course, if Anno-san does it, anything will become Eva. In short, if Mr.¬†Eva‚Äôs hands touch it, then it‚Äôs Eva!‚Äù<a href="#fn77" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref77"><sup>77</sup></a> The conversation we‚Äôre having now really goes hand in hand with that.<a href="#fn78" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref78"><sup>78</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> If we assume it‚Äôs possible that there‚Äôs some sort of logical basis [for Eva], then of course it‚Äôs ‚ÄúHideaki Anno‚Äù. Accordingly, parts [of Eva] emerge that even those of us who are very close [to Eva/Anno] don‚Äôt understand well. To be honest, [Eva is] like a ‚Äúblack box‚Äù, and so there are many occasions when I am convinced that a particular way is ‚ÄúEva-esque‚Äù and it turns out not to be.</p>
<p>‚Äî Only, more than ten years have passed since the 1995 version [of Eva], and Anno-san himself has changed, right?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Naturally, I also expected that, for the ‚ÄúNew Theatrical Edition‚Äù, because Hideaki Anno has changed with age, Eva will change as well, but‚Ä¶ This is also [just] my own speculation, but in truth he has probably not changed much at all. I feel like nothing has changed since he was a middle school student watching Ultraman and [Space Battleship] Yamato. There is a ‚Äúswitch‚Äù in Anno-san‚Äôs mind that is completely unchanged, a switch constantly clicking back and forth between two alternatives. Of course, in the man himself, there is a desire to change. For this reason Mari was introduced, and he wanted [things] to be changed, but ‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚Äî That [desire] includes the ‚Äúspirit of service‚Äù which wants to live up to the expectations of the audience, right?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> That‚Äôs also probably there. Only, with regards to the new films, the circumstances are unique, and unlike what has happened up until now. Anno-san is the original creator, the scriptwriter, the chief director, the producer (substantially), the sponsor<a href="#fn79" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref79"><sup>79</sup></a>, the head of the production studio, and he also overlooks distribution and advertising; it‚Äôs an awe-inspiring situation. Every final decision is being made by him alone. In his capacity as producer and chief director, Anno-san believed that he had to introduce Mari and change the story; however, as the original creator, scriptwriter, and author, he did not want to make the changes. I think that, more than a resistance to change, he had the feeling that if he changed Eva it would somehow not be ‚Äúhis‚Äù Eva, and so he was divided. Even though he knew that the story would inevitably have to change if he introduced a new character, preserving the essence [of Evangelion] while having that new character play an active role was a great problem.</p>
<p>‚Äî This resistance, or should I say conflict, paid off, and, in the end, somehow this broken ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù took form, right? ???<a href="#fn80" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref80"><sup>80</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Ultimately, I think that [the film] forthrightly expressed what Anno-san had stated, that ‚ÄúShinji truly doesn‚Äôt want to pilot‚Äù. As a result, the story clearly differed from my interpretation of episode 19 as ‚ÄúShinji truly knowing that he has to pilot, and so piloting in the end‚Äù.<a href="#fn81" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref81"><sup>81</sup></a></p>
</section>
<section id="part-7-1" class="level3">
<h3>Part 7</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=411903#411903">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=411903#411903</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Entrusting the third Rei‚Äôs distant feelings<a href="#fn82" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref82"><sup>82</sup></a> / The feelings [I] attempted to entrust to [express through?] the third Rei<a href="#fn83" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref83"><sup>83</sup></a> <a href="#fn84" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref84"><sup>84</sup></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>‚Äî At what point did you decide that the climax would blend the story of episode 19 with elements of episode 23?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> I had suggested that this would be a good idea, and it was [in place] from a very early stage. The original plan had been for ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù to comprise episodes eight to nineteen. I thought this would be difficult. If the number of episodes covered would be large in any case, I thought we should instead increase the range to include episode 23, and free up the third part onwards. I thought it would be unpleasant to leave ‚Äúhomework‚Äù.</p>
<p>‚Äî So you could admit new elements in the future?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Right. There was a feeling that we wanted the difficulties to be, as far as possible, confined to ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù, because we wanted a situation where we would be able to try various things in the third part. So, after Rei‚Äôs death in episode 23, Kaworu comes to Shinji; we attempted a structure similar to the TV series. But, in the end, Rei didn‚Äôt die‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚Äî Instead, it seemed that Shinji and Rei ‚Äúgot together‚Äù.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> There is probably some other intention there, so I think you should check with Anno-san [about that]. However, because there was a feeling that Rei III had been poorly developed in the TV series, after Rei II died in ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù, we wanted to develop in detail the drama of Rei III in ‚ÄúQ‚Äù [<em>3.0</em>].</p>
<p>‚Äî So it‚Äôs something you were not able to fully realize in the TV series. ‚ÄúBecause I am the third‚Äù is an amazingly impactful, famous line of dialogue, but, in truth, I felt that [Rei III] didn‚Äôt really mean much after that‚Ä¶</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> I thought going deeply into that would be interesting, even in a ‚ÄúScience Fiction‚Äù-like way. As Rei realizes the fact, and the significance of the fact, that there has been more than one Rei before her, how, as a clone, will she achieve her independence as an individual? I wanted to develop a story like that. However, it was decided that Rei wouldn‚Äôt die, and, in the climax of ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù, we strongly and actively push the idea of ‚ÄúRei and Shinji being brought together‚Äù, a development taken over from ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù.</p>
<p>‚Äî That was an extraordinarily surprising development.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Because it‚Äôs even linked with the motivation for having Asuka pilot Unit-03, it ended up being a stronger way of developing things than I thought. ??<a href="#fn85" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref85"><sup>85</sup></a></p>
<p>‚Äî There‚Äôs one thing that mystified me. Despite the fact that the original scenario for the climax was different, in ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù Gendou mentions something like a ‚Äúlove love strategy‚Äù intended to bring Rei and Shinji closer together. Why does that appear to be consistent [with ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù]?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Anno-san probably hasn‚Äôt thought about that very deeply.</p>
<p>‚Äî Eh? That wasn‚Äôt foreshadowing?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> We on the staff had a conversation about that dialogue from ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù, wondering if it was okay to have [Gendou] say that. Not to mention that I thought Rei II was going to die in ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù.</p>
<p>‚Äî Then why, despite that, was there a consistency?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> This is evidence that the story was developed, not with an ‚Äúinductive‚Äù technique, but with a ‚Äúdeductive‚Äù one. ‚ÄúHe already said it there, so we have no choice‚Äù. It‚Äôs something like a methodology where [the story] is adjusted, even forcibly, to be consistent with what has already been done.</p>
<p>‚Äî This is quite a shock (laughing)! Surely, immediately following ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù, there are people who grin and say of the ‚Äúlove love strategy‚Äù, ‚ÄúThis is a big change!‚Äù Surely it leaves a strong impression on everyone. As a result, they will surely think during ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù, ‚ÄúAh, as I thought, those two were brought together!‚Äù</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> The impression that Anno-san mainly wanted to convey was that Gendou and Fuyutsuki were devising a secret plot. Because Shinji happens to go to Rei‚Äôs room just after that, that was what they discussed. When ‚Äúsecret plot‚Äù and ‚ÄúShinji and Rei‚Äù were combined, it probably appeared something like ‚Äúa strategy to bring together Shinji and Rei‚Äù.</p>
<p>‚Äî Rather than being disappointed, I‚Äôm impressed. All the more, I have a pleasant feeling that things have become ‚ÄúEva-esque‚Äù. The fact that this consistency is inherent [makes it] extremely valuable; I am delighted [to think] that this may be the much-discussed ‚Äúlive feeling‚Äù.<a href="#fn86" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref86"><sup>86</sup></a> In any case, there will surely be many viewers who have the impression that, this time, Gendo‚Äôs Human Instrumentality Project [somehow depends on] this ‚Äúlove love strategy‚Äù. Fuyutsuki also says something like, ‚ÄúAs we thought, owing to those two Unit-01 has awakened‚Äù.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> And Gendou replies something like ‚ÄúA little while longer, and our project is complete‚Äù. I had doubts storyboarding that conversation, and sent Anno-san a series of questions about it. ‚ÄúSo Gendou knew this would happen to Unit-01? Or was Gendou also surprised and troubled? Or was Gendou surprised, but pleased with the outcome?‚Äù I didn‚Äôt understand the specific meaning of the statement, so I struggled to interpret it. Anno-san replied that, ‚ÄúFor now, we‚Äôll say he aimed at this and things went the way he expected‚Äù. I wondered if that was enough. For myself, I am still skeptical that even Gendou isn‚Äôt really panicking inside, but‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚Äî So [everything] will probably be overturned again next time?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> That is perfectly likely (laughs).</p>
<p>‚Äî One more thing: Kaworu‚Äôs existence in light of the fact that we are given this strong impression that, ‚Äúthis time, the human instrumentality project was this ‚Äòlove love strategy‚Äô with Shinji and Rei‚Äù. There‚Äôs no doubt that female fans were extremely pleased by Kaworu‚Äôs line after the ending: ‚ÄúIkari Shinji-kun, this time, I will make you happy‚Äù.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Kaworu‚Äôs line stayed the same from the very first storyboard. It was something he said while wearing his usual relaxed smile. Of course, at the last minute, just, I think, before we started post-synchronization, we began talking about whether or not it would be better if Kaworu looked scary during that scene.</p>
<p>‚Äî As a result, it looks like he‚Äôs come to take his bride by force!<a href="#fn87" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref87"><sup>87</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Right, right (laughing). [We thought it would be] more interesting if Kaworu looked like [he was thinking]: ‚ÄúYou‚Äôve been with a woman while I‚Äôve been away? How dare you‚Ä¶!‚Äù It‚Äôs not Kaworu‚Äôs usual relaxed expression; he‚Äôs somehow become irritated, right?</p>
</section>
<section id="part-8-1" class="level3">
<h3>Part 8</h3>
</section>
<section id="part-9-1" class="level3">
<h3>Part 9</h3>
