<section id="part-10-1" class="level3">
<h3>Part 10</h3>
</section>
<section id="part-11" class="level3">
<h3>Part 11</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=439170#439170">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=439170#439170</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>The significantly changed Angels of ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù</p>
</blockquote>
<p>‚Äî This time around, the designs of the Angels, such as the ‚ÄúHeiwajima-like‚Äù seventh Angel, have all radically changed. Was this the intention from the outset?<a href="#fn88" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref88"><sup>88</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> As far as the seventh Angel is concerned, the truth is that the original reason [for the change in design] was that the genga for that episode had been entirely lost, and we couldn‚Äôt use the ‚ÄòBANK.‚Äô If the genga had remained, even if the key animation director decided to redo them, episode eight would probably have remained [in the film] in its entirety. [We thought,] if we can‚Äôt make use of the genga, let‚Äôs completely change Asuka‚Äôs introductory scene. The design was put together by Shigeto Koyama-san and Daizen Komatsuda-kun [‚Ä¶].<a href="#fn89" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref89"><sup>89</sup></a></p>
<p>‚Äî Who did the design for the eighth Angel?<a href="#fn90" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref90"><sup>90</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> The design of the falling Angel was done entirely by Mahiro Maeda-san; the design of the humanoid that emerges from its center was done by [Takeshi] Honda-kun. It was a part I didn‚Äôt supervise, so I don‚Äôt know the details, but I think the CG was relatively difficult. With the sixth Angel in ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù, even if things weren‚Äôt perfect, we could somehow see what we had done correctly, and figure out how to proceed in a way that would bring us closer to our goal. However, with the falling Angel, it seems that things were more or less done by trial and error, with no goal in sight.<a href="#fn91" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref91"><sup>91</sup></a></p>
<p>‚Äî The third Angel‚Äôs design [was done by] <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bokurano" title="Wikipedia: Bokurano">Bokurano</a></em> author <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mohiro%20Kitoh" title="Wikipedia: Mohiro Kitoh">Mohiro Kitoh</a>-san, right?<a href="#fn92" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref92"><sup>92</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> That‚Äôs right. Anno had done a rough sketch, but the idea that Kitoh-san submitted seemed nearly definitive on the first attempt.<a href="#fn93" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref93"><sup>93</sup></a></p>
<p>‚Äî [‚Ä¶] why was the design of the tenth Angel altered?<a href="#fn94" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref94"><sup>94</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> I don‚Äôt know the reason. I think, at the earliest stage of plot development, that even the fact that it would change form had not been determined. Originally, the design of the TV series‚Äô fourteenth Angel contained excellent ideas. The folding fan-paper style arms were especially interesting. That conception appeared from the beginning, to the extent that, in the proposal for the TV series, there was an image board where Unit-01 battled an Angel that was just a flying [pair of] origami-like arms.<a href="#fn95" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref95"><sup>95</sup></a> I don‚Äôt really know the reason that was changed.<a href="#fn96" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref96"><sup>96</sup></a></p>
<p>‚Äî In episode 19 of the TV series, Eva consumes the Angel, but, in ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù, the Angel consumes Eva. I think this reversal is impressive. The audience will be first of all surprised by the change in form, and then doubly surprised by the act of consumption. I think this Angel might symbolize ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù.<a href="#fn97" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref97"><sup>97</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> It‚Äôs different than the direct consumption in the battle with Unit-03. We used an idea where the impression would be of something resembling the act of a predatory animal. If it had been a TV series, a week would have passed in between, so it probably wouldn‚Äôt matter, but in a film, I thought that having a scene conveying a similar impression just thirty minutes prior would have been awkward. [More than transforming, it felt like it was gradually developing. It seemed like the Angel was gradually coming closer to a human being. ??] Even though we had started the storyboards, the design was changing day by day without being solidified. Even in the storyboards, at different periods a variety of types and different designs were used. As for the Angel‚Äôs final form, I wanted to do something resembling a female villain from the Sentai Series. I still feel that way.<a href="#fn98" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref98"><sup>98</sup></a></p>
<p>‚Äî Eh, you mean [with some sort of] headgear?<a href="#fn99" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref99"><sup>99</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Yeah. Similar to Riderman [from Kamen Rider]. From the mouth to the nose you would have the face of a woman, and the head from the eyes upwards would be covered by the Angel. The body would be nude and enormous. When I submitted this proposal, it was immediately rejected (laughs). In the Sentai Series, there are the scenes where [the villain/monster] grows enormous on the other side of the mountains [?] and rages violently, right? Using ‚Äú<em>muriyara na gousei</em>‚Äù<a href="#fn100" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref100"><sup>100</sup></a> [you have the villain/monster] kicking around styrofoam boulders, [and so on]. [It was] this sort of image, but when I showed the drawing to Anno-san, he naturally thought it was no good. If I was to say which I prefer, I‚Äôm someone who enjoys the Sentai Series even more than Kamen Rider, but probably Anno only enjoys the Sentai Series as a joke, and doesn‚Äôt seriously like them. However, I think we ended up with an interesting design.<a href="#fn101" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref101"><sup>101</sup></a></p>
<p>‚Äî The battle with the Angel used the same ‚Äú<em>katto wari</em>‚Äù<a href="#fn102" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref102"><sup>102</sup></a> as in episode 19 of the TV series. For example, the most impressive cut where Unit-01 rushes into the command center [is the same].<a href="#fn103" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref103"><sup>103</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> That part was the same as it was in the [original] storyboards; beyond the change in design of the Angel, we treated things in such a way so as to only modify those parts we had to change. At first we thought that the ‚Äúkatto wari‚Äù should be completely changed, but it wouldn‚Äôt have gone well if we had changed it. For me, changing episode 19 was extremely stressful in and of itself; I felt like the more we changed it, the more the quality [of the sequence] would suffer.<a href="#fn104" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref104"><sup>104</sup></a></p>
</section>
<section id="part-12" class="level3">
<h3>Part 12</h3>
</section>
<section id="part-13" class="level3">
<h3>Part 13</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=429536#429536">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=429536#429536</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Casting That Stressed The Element Of Surprise</p>
</blockquote>
<p>‚Äî I‚Äôm going to bring the subject [of the conversation] back, once more, to Mari. I‚Äôd like to ask you about the selection of Maaya Sakamoto-san [for the role]. Around when was the casting [for Mari‚Äôs role] discussed?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> The decision was made almost at the last minute. As far as Mari was concerned, Anno-san was, on the whole, extremely circumspect. Maybe it was less circumspection, than the fact that, from a certain stage, [he thought] it would be better if he didn‚Äôt decide [about Mari]. Perhaps he thought, ‚ÄúIf I make the decisions, of course she won‚Äôt end up being the character who destroys Eva‚Äù ‚Ä¶ I don‚Äôt really know.</p>
<p>Even concerning the [voice] actor‚Äôs selection - first of all, Mari‚Äôs character had remained unsettled the whole way up to that point. Just prior to voice recording, at a period when, if we didn‚Äôt decide [on an actor] we wouldn‚Äôt be able to make an offer - even though we had reached such a stage, we received no indication from Anno-san as to his desires or the direction [in which we should proceed]. Having no other choice, at the end of last year Sadamoto-san and I discussed things at the level of a ‚Äústanding conversation‚Äù, raising the names of as many actors as the two of us could come up with, one after the other, responding [to each] with things like, ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs a possibility‚Äù, or ‚ÄúThat won‚Äôt work‚Äù, and going on and on like this forever. It was then that Sakamoto-san‚Äôs name first appeared.</p>
<p>‚Äî Given <em>Aim For The Top 2!</em>, anime fans would be likely to conjecture that you and Sadamoto-san would decide upon Maaya Sakamoto-san.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> I‚Äôm sorry [to say that] we didn‚Äôt think along those lines at all. I don‚Äôt mean to be rude; Sakamoto-san‚Äôs name came up much later in the conversations between Sadamoto-san and I‚Ä¶ Even though the [nature of Mari‚Äôs] character had not been indicated [to the staff] by Anno-san, the work of producing [the film‚Äôs] storyboards had continued. I had no choice but to portray Mari [in the storyboards] according to my own definition [of her character]; [I saw her as] an ‚Äúirresponsible‚Äù<a href="#fn105" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref105"><sup>105</sup></a> and ‚Äúcunning‚Äù<a href="#fn106" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref106"><sup>106</sup></a> character. [To say] ‚Äúcowardice‚Äù<a href="#fn107" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref107"><sup>107</sup></a> would be wrong; it was a ‚Äúcunningness‚Äù<a href="#fn108" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref108"><sup>108</sup></a> at the opposite remove from ‚Äúdiligence‚Äù<a href="#fn109" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref109"><sup>109</sup></a>, ‚Äúobstinacy‚Äù<a href="#fn110" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref110"><sup>110</sup></a>, and so on - or could I say it was a feeling of ‚Äúthe right mix of seasonings?‚Äù<a href="#fn111" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref111"><sup>111</sup></a> ‚Ä¶ I thought that, otherwise, she would overlap [with] the existing Eva characters and be lost among them.</p>
<p>Anno-san had previously said, ‚ÄúAll the characters that appear in Eva are me‚Äù; he said that not just Shinji, but Kaji and Misato as well, and even characters like Kaworu and Rei, are aspects of himself. In this sense, every character is ultimately the same. On the surface, different ‚Äúseasonings‚Äù have been used, but inside [the characters] really are very similar. If Mari were to end up the same as them, she would not be able to destroy that world. As a result, for me, Mari was a girl who made use of that ‚Äúfrivolousness‚Äù<a href="#fn112" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref112"><sup>112</sup></a> that was the opposite of diligence for her own benefit.</p>
<p>‚Äî [She] has lines [in the film] that give that impression. ‚ÄúIn [my] own interest‚Äù‚Ä¶</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> However, that would be the exact opposite of Sakamoto-san‚Äôs natural tendencies [as a voice actor]. Sakamoto-san herself is the same way. [You get] the impression that the characters Sakamoto-san has played up until now are honor students and ‚Äúdiligent‚Äù [individuals]. Because of that [I] didn‚Äôt think of Sakamoto-san‚Äôs name.</p>
<p>‚Äî But, instead, [you thought] the opposite [type] was suited for the role?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Yeah. When Sadamoto-san brought up Sakamoto-san‚Äôs name, I thought, ‚Äúthat might be interesting‚Äù. During the first casting in 1995, we appointed (Megumi) Hayashibara-san [to play] a silent and melancholy girl, and offered (Kotono) Mitsuishi-san a female character who was a twenty-nine year old adult; that was almost inconceivable at the time. There was an element of surprise there, and [that] was impressive. The combination of Mari and Sakamoto-san suddenly reminded us of that time; it resembled [those decisions].</p>
<p>Nevertheless, [we] were extremely uneasy [about it]. Anno-san had no concerns about the ability of Sakamoto-san herself, and he finds it interesting when the voice doesn‚Äôt match the style of character,<a href="#fn113" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref113"><sup>113</sup></a> so, when we suggested [to Anno,] ‚Äúhow would Maaya Sakamoto-san be?‚Äù, [he responded] something like, ‚ÄúGood! Good!‚Äù, and it was settled.</p>
<p>‚Äî [He] responded immediately?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Yeah. However, I don‚Äôt really know whether he thought deeply about it [personally], or whether [he just thought that] whatever Sadamoto-san and myself decided upon would be good (laughs).</p>
</section>
<section id="part-14" class="level3">
<h3>Part 14</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>The Presence of a Voice Which Penetrates the Character<a href="#fn114" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref114"><sup>114</sup></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>‚Äî You actually witnessed the voice recording sessions. How did they go?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> I was worried, even as we reached the day appointed for the sessions. Until we tried matching a voice with the picture, [we] were completely unable to say how the [role of the] pre-title sequence, something like ‚Äúa young girl who fights while humming to herself‚Äù, should be performed. Usually, [we] somehow arrive at a conjecture. If [the actor is] performing a character that resembles something done previously, then [we] have a general sense of it, only this time [we] couldn‚Äôt even form an impression - should [Sakamoto] perform with an ‚Äúadult‚Äù voice or a ‚Äúgirlish‚Äù voice?<a href="#fn115" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref115"><sup>115</sup></a> [‚Ä¶] Was the ‚Äúmismatch‚Äù we were aiming at really going to cause an interesting ‚Äúchemical reaction‚Äù, or‚Ä¶? However, in the very first test, I was already grinning hearing her voice appended to the ‚Äúfast cut‚Äù. In my heart I was thinking, ‚Äúvictory!‚Äù</p>
<p>‚Äî I was also present on that occasion. The [very] first shot at a test for the pre-title sequence was good, right? It‚Äôs amazing that her delivery on the first cut [produced] a perfect test.</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> That test was truly amazing, to the extent that there were cuts already being approved by the chief director at the test. We recorded multiple takes afterwards, but we almost entirely settled on the direction of the first test.</p>
<p>‚Äî What sort of difficulties related to Mari were there in the performance?</p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> Concerning the pre-title sequence, after the final version of the storyboards was submitted and we had met to discuss producing the images, Mari‚Äôs dialogue was almost completely revised. As a result, not only the dramatic role, but the personality [of the character] changed. In this way, because she was a character created in a state of indecision, it could seem that she was a different character in each scene she appeared in. Someone designated a ‚Äúproblem child‚Äù, a girl who can pilot Eva with pleasure and without protest; she hums to herself while fighting, and when it comes down to it and she gives her all, cries ‚Äú<em>Ora ora</em>!‚Äù<a href="#fn116" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref116"><sup>116</sup></a> and impales the angel, saying that even her pain is exciting; with great zeal she finishes [the angel] off despite the exchange of blows, and politely thanks Unit-05 for its efforts. I felt dizzy when this character emerged from Anno-san‚Äôs revisions. I couldn‚Äôt help thinking that, even in this short pre-title sequence, the character was divided [into multiple personalities]. Like in the storyboards, she would be wearing a helmet that hid her facial expressions, so it wouldn‚Äôt be clear if she was speaking seriously or messing around. Even when I asked [Anno] for an explanation, he gave me nothing but vague responses. I think it was probably quite a difficult role for Sakamoto-san as well. Owing to this state of affairs, at a single glance [everything] might appear to be ‚Äúblurred‚Äù, with pieces scattered everywhere. [We] wanted a voice that would convince [us] that all [these elements] were present within a single young girl.</p>
<p>That being the case, there were already no problems with her acting technique. That was probably already settled before she stepped in front of the microphone. This [question of technique] is interesting as well. The relationship between the actors of Eva and their characters, and their relationship to Anno-san, is completely different than a in normal production. It‚Äôs unique, I think, in that it incorporates feelings lying adjacent to reality. It no longer has anything to do with skill or lack of skill. It‚Äôs not because the technique is masterful or because the quality of the voice is good. It‚Äôs not just to provide what is being requested; if there‚Äôs nothing in [the performance] that transforms the very work itself, then‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚Äî [‚Ä¶] I think, owing to Maaya Sakamoto-san‚Äôs voice being inserted into the film, another ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù-like change occurred.<a href="#fn117" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref117"><sup>117</sup></a></p>
<p><code>Tsurumaki:</code> I thought that was really good. [Mari] was different than the characters Sakamoto-san has portrayed up until now, and, from the impression [I received] at the test, she had practiced considerably [for the role]. I wonder if this is acceptable for a director, but, when [Sakamoto‚Äôs] voice came in, it was like I understood Mari for the first time.</p>
</section>
</section>
<section id="commentary-from-designers" class="level2">
<h2>Commentary From Designers</h2>
<section id="third-angelmohiro-kitoh" class="level3">
<h3>Third Angel/Mohiro Kitoh</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/post/435007/Evangelion-20-Complete-Records-Collection/#435007">http://forum.evageeks.org/post/435007/Evangelion-20-Complete-Records-Collection/#435007</a></p>
<p>Anno-san first asked me about doing some work for him around the spring of 2004, on a different project than Eva. He asked me about the design for the third angel of ‚ÄúBreak‚Äù around the end of 2006, quite some time before the release of ‚ÄúPrelude.‚Äù</p>
<p>To be honest, the third angel is fundamentally the same as it was in Anno-san‚Äôs sketch. My job was not quite that of a designer. [‚Ä¶]</p>
<p>I came up with a form like this, following Anno-san‚Äôs outline in a routine manner, so there was no difficulty with the design. In addition, I was told from the beginning that CG would be used to animate its movement, so I didn‚Äôt bother contriving something [new] that would be easy to draw. Instead, I put the [existing] parts in order so that the CG modeling would be easy. However, I have no knowledge of [the process], so I don‚Äôt actually know whether that made it easier or not. Another reason was that I heard that the angel would only be on screen for five minutes, so I thought it wasn‚Äôt necessary to waste a lot of time doing the design.</p>
<p>The insect-like legs were also in Anno‚Äôs sketch. I attached them half-way up the torso so that you could imagine what the form of the angel was like before it was captured. The design was completed at the end of 2006, and the rest was up to others. I was no longer involved. Nor had I indicated how it would move. When I saw the finished film I thought, ‚Äúso this is how it moves‚Äù: its feet clattering around, and its neck and tail acting just like a pair of wings. I was impressed. I felt like it had been done by an animator with a great sensitivity to movement.</p>
<p>When it comes to the things I design for my own manga, I have all the specifications within me, and I make as many changes [to them] as I like while sketching the draft. Most of my designs are done off-the-cuff on the draft paper. However, when it comes to a job like this, where I am designing something for another person to use, I can‚Äôt fully know everything that is required, so there will surely be things I will have to apologize for. [?]</p>
<p>As mine was a special case where I did the work without coming into the workplace, I felt like I couldn‚Äôt completely grasp how far I should be involved in the plans for actually rendering it and obviously related problems like [the question of] its movement. That‚Äôs the reason why I handed the work over at that stage, once the [angel‚Äôs] form was set out. I know the best thing about this sort of job is going to the office and playing catchball there while you finish your work, but the fact that I could by no means accept that schedule owing to my job writing manga made things difficult. Although I only did this much, my name was listed in the credits. I feel terrible about that.</p>
