<section id="seventh-angelshigeto-koyama" class="level3">
<h3>Seventh Angel/Shigeto Koyama</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=436453#436453">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=436453#436453</a></p>
<p>Rough sketches for settei/Shigeto Koyama</p>
<p>Speculations on the structure of the head, midsection, etc.</p>
<p>Directions for 3D CG model brush-up/Daizen Komatsuda (pp.¬†147-148)</p>
<p>I was called in after (Daizen) Komatsuda-san‚Äôs ‚ÄúHeiwajima‚Äù concept was OKed by Anno-san. Even beforehand, I really loved the magnificent designs of the angels, and had thought at some length about what design elements would be necessary to establish something as an angel. The impetus which enabled my answer was a ‚ÄúVira Seijin‚Äù ballpoint pen I received when I visited the home of scriptwriter Yoji Enokido-san. After studying Toru Narita-san‚Äôs designs of monsters and space aliens for <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ultraman" title="Wikipedia: Ultraman">Ultraman</a></em> and <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ultra%20Seven" title="Wikipedia: Ultra Seven">Ultra Seven</a></em>, I noticed [he used] a sculptural design: a ‚Äúlinear‚Äù, ‚Äúgeometrical‚Äù shape consisting of ‚Äúsurfaces‚Äù with depth. [*]</p>
<p>Moreover, when I worked on director Tsurumaki-san‚Äôs <em>Aim for the Top 2!</em> [<em>Diebuster</em>], I personally wanted to make an effort to link the designs [of that work] to those of Anno-san‚Äôs prior work, <em>Aim for the Top!</em> [<em>Gunbuster</em>], so I thoroughly studied ‚ÄúAnno design‚Äù and ‚ÄúAnno detail‚Äù by looking at settei and individual frames [from that work]. Because of that experience, I was able to grasp that the disposition of triangles and hexagons was a crucial element [of Anno‚Äôs design]. [*]</p>
<p>As a result, I considered there to be two design requirements for an angel: the design should be ‚Äúsculptural‚Äù and ‚Äúcontain triangles and hexagons.‚Äù Furthermore, I suggested a third requirement: ‚Äúits actions exceed human reason.‚Äù The idea that its floating feet would seem to ‚Äúrend‚Äù the air like ‚Äúdividers‚Äù, [?] leave tracks of ice, and walk upon the surface of the water was [for the sake of] this third, ‚Äúbehavioral‚Äù requirement. I found Komatsuda-san‚Äôs ‚ÄúHeiwajima‚Äù concept<a href="#fn118" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref118"><sup>118</sup></a> personally interesting, [‚Ä¶]<a href="#fn119" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref119"><sup>119</sup></a></p>
<p>Furthermore, Anno-san brought up the image of the Toshiba IHI pavilion at Osaka <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expo%20%2770" title="Wikipedia: Expo '70">Expo ‚Äô70</a><a href="#fn120" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref120"><sup>120</sup></a> (designed by Kisho Kurokawa) - I was thinking, ‚ÄúThe tetra-frame is a polygon! At last!‚Äù and was privately delighted (laughs). So, I submitted a rough design showing a hexagonal shape comprised of tetra-frames, and [the idea] was OKed.</p>
<p>For the face, I submitted various patterns along the lines of a design by Yoshito Asari-san, the ‚Äúinorganic‚Äù, ‚Äúexpressionless,‚Äù ‚Äúegoless‚Äù character of which inspired dread. [*] The new designs of the provisional Unit-05 and the third angel during the pre-title sequence would, as the opening strike, surprise the viewers, so I thought that there should be an angel design which could reassure the viewers a bit, like, ‚Äúwithout doubt, this is Eva!‚Äù I decided upon the colors - black and white, with red mixed in - using the same rationale. At the stage where the face was decided, an idea of Anno-san‚Äôs - ‚Äúit should move like a clock, ‚Äòkaku, kaku‚Äô‚Äù - was incorporated. We converted the confirmed image into a 3D model. What we made adjustments to on the monitor became the final design.</p>
<section id="sketches-1" class="level4">
<h4>Sketches</h4>
<p>[I found Komatsuda‚Äôs handwriting quite difficult to read, so I haven‚Äôt tried to do the notes (at least, not yet).]</p>
<p><img height="598" src="../images/eva/2010-crc/clockiel1.jpg" title="http://img27.imageshack.us/img27/7380/clockiel1.jpg" width="800"/> <img height="580" src="../images/eva/2010-crc/clockiel2.jpg" title="http://img857.imageshack.us/img857/5905/clockiel2.jpg" width="800"/> <img height="741" src="../images/eva/2010-crc/clockiel3.jpg" title="http://img607.imageshack.us/img607/1664/clockiel3.jpg" width="800"/></p>
</section>
</section>
<section id="tenth-angelyoshito-asari" class="level3">
<h3>Tenth Angel/Yoshito Asari</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=437736#437736">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=437736#437736</a></p>
<p>The design was requested early on. For ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù, considerable changes were made to the battle with the sixth angel, which became the core of the work. For ‚ÄúBreak,‚Äù the battle with the tenth angel was supposed to correspond to that [climactic battle with the sixth]. [‚Ä¶] I wonder if [Anno] just wanted something concrete to be used, temporarily, as an impetus for creating the ‚Äúgimmicks,‚Äù battles, and so on, for the new parts of the work. As a result, in ‚ÄúBreak,‚Äù major innovations were incorporated into every angel battle.</p>
<p>Up until now, with the exception of the TV series‚Äô third angel, the angel design requests that I have received have all been explained with reference to a ‚Äúgimmick‚Äù within the work (the fourth angel has beam-like whips for arms, the fourteenth angel has folded fabric-like ‚Äúcutters‚Äù for arms, and so on). As far as the initial request for the new version of the strongest angel, I only remember the vague description: ‚ÄúSomething like [the fourteenth angel in the TV series] appears; in reality it is something completely different.‚Äù To begin with, I submitted an idea where [‚ÄúBreak‚Äôs‚Äù tenth angel] appears looking like the fourteenth angel of the TV series, with [a pair of] ‚Äúbelt-like‚Äù arms wrapped around its body. When it unwraps itself, its form completely changes. After that, it is completely different than the TV series‚Äô fourteenth angel, with a terrifying shape ‚Ä¶ when I drew the angel, that was what I had in mind.</p>
<p>I submitted the first draft, and completely forgot about it until the beginning of 2007, when a rough sketch<a href="#fn121" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref121"><sup>121</sup></a> from the director suddenly arrived, with the following written upon it: ‚ÄúLike something wound upon a reel.‚Äù ‚ÄúLike the upper parts of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/King%20Joe%20%28Ultra%20monster%29" title="Wikipedia: King Joe (Ultra monster)">King Joe</a>?‚Äù ‚ÄúSomething consumed by the angel emerges.‚Äù To begin with, I thought about something that would incorporate that ‚Äúgimmick.‚Äù I submitted an idea where, concerning the ‚Äúconsumption‚Äù, it extends a proboscis, penetrates the Eva, and draws out its insides.</p>
<p>There were further changes after that [‚Ä¶] In the fourth draft the ‚Äúgimmick‚Äù of the battle solidified, [?] and an idea was presented where the angel transformed from its ‚Äúfluttering‚Äù condition, rolling up into a solid pipe, or else changing into the form of a spear. There was a design change in accordance with that.</p>
<p>The change where the absorbed Eva protruded from the [angel‚Äôs] body itself was also a directoral request. Along with the disappearance of the torso in the design, the ‚Äúfluttering‚Äù was changed to resemble the palm of a hand. [‚Ä¶] it seemed like an image where the absorbed Eva was manipulated like a puppet. [?] At that time the challenge was putting into effect an idea where the form, or, should I say, the texture of the whole, suddenly changes. From <em>funyaan</em> to <em>shakiin</em> [‚Äúlimp‚Äù to ‚Äúfirm‚Äù?]; that was the verbal instruction given by the director.</p>
<p>As far as Ayanami‚Äôs absorption was concerned, the instructions came from the director as well. I myself thought about a design where the entire body didn‚Äôt emerge, but you would have the torso without the arms, or an asymmetry where an arm emerges in place of a leg, or where the body parts ‚Äúcross‚Äù one another. However, when I tried drawing it, it wasn‚Äôt as good as I expected.</p>
<p>I tried drawing various things, and left the final decision to the director.</p>
