<section class="footnotes">
<hr/>
<ol>
<li id="fn1"><p>Lit. ‚Äúestablishment‚Äù. As far as I understand it, ‚Äúsettei‚Äù refers to all designs, drawings, and information used to establish or flesh out the world of the animation and its characters, and to inform and direct the process of animation itself.<a href="#fnref1">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn2"><p>Lit. ‚Äúphotography‚Äù - process of converting cels to film. I believe CG and so on is added at this time. ‚ÄìEditor<a href="#fnref2">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn3"><p>Lit. ‚Äúoriginal images‚Äù or ‚Äúprimary images‚Äù - key animation cels (I believe). ‚ÄìEditor<a href="#fnref3">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn4"><p>I‚Äôm not very familiar with the term; see NAveryW‚Äôs reply below:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>‚ÄúAn animatic is basically the storyboard set as‚Ä¶ not quite an animation, but timed to how the final movie will look. It usually has voice-overs and sometimes sound effects and music. It‚Äôs also known as a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/leica%20reel" title="Wikipedia: leica reel">leica reel</a>‚Äù.</p>
</blockquote>
<a href="#fnref4">‚Ü©</a></li>
<li id="fn5"><p>‚Äúhe‚Äôs a CM director who is credited in the Rebuild films as Anno‚Äôs assistant and also as being involved in publicity or advertising. In the interviews so far he‚Äôs been mentioned as taking notes at Atami [see <a href="#memo-1">Enokido Memo 1</a>] and modifying one of the 1.0 posters according to Anno‚Äôs directions‚Äù. <a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=438684#438684">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=438684#438684</a><a href="#fnref5">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn6"><p>‚ÄúTo be honest, my first instinct was to translate „ÄéËâØ„ÅÑ„Ç≠„É£„É©„Äè as‚Äùreal character‚Äú, where‚Äùgood&quot; means ‚Äúwell-developed‚Äù. So, ‚Äúreal character‚Äù or ‚Äúwell-developed character‚Äù. On the other hand, the context seemed to suggest that maybe Tsurumaki was proposing softening Asuka‚Äôs character so that the audience couldn‚Äôt fail to become emotionally invested in her before the Unit-03 sequence. In the end, I felt unsure, so I just translated it literally. I think symbv would certainly understand the remark, but I‚Äôm not 100% sure what it meant‚Äú. <a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=461297#461297">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=461297#461297</a></p>
<p>[symbv] ‚Äú‚Ä¶I would lean towards a translation to‚Äùgood character&quot; as well. It allows all the ambiguity to stay intact. As for interpretation, I would go for making audience emotionally invested in Asuka deeper. I have not seen Rebuild but from the examples he gave and what I already knew about the food party, I would say that they wanted to make Asuka a ‚Äúnice girl‚Äù whom Shinji could feel certain empathy, and thus gave him the ‚Äúshock and sense of loss‚Äù on Touji‚Äôs level (whom Shinji definitely had close relationship with) as in the series‚Äú. <a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=461351#461351">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=461351#461351</a><a href="#fnref6">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn7"><p><a href="http://www.urbandictionary.com/define.php?term=Death%20Flag">Urban Dictionary</a> defines it as</p>
<blockquote>
<p>‚ÄúAn instance where a character is subject to extreme danger foreshadowed with grim implications. Examples of death flagging:</p>
<ul>
<li>Unknowingly ticking off a unstable individual.</li>
<li>Wondering into a zone at the wrong time.</li>
<li>Taking on a dangerous deed with slim chances of success.</li>
<li>Short sighted approach to a ludicrous event.&quot;</li>
</ul>
</blockquote>
<p>The NSFW site <a href="http://danbooru.donmai.us/post/index?tags=death_flag">Danbooru</a> defines it as</p>
<blockquote>
<p>‚Äú<em>(Shibou Furagu)</em> A sign to the audience that a character is going to die. A death flag is usually raised by such things as saying or doing something that can be seen as tempting fate, a character doing something that he or she has been warned (sometimes repeatedly) will lead to death, an unrequited relationship finally being requited, etc.‚Äù</p>
</blockquote>
<p>See also TvTropes on <a href="http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TemptingFate">‚ÄúTempting Fate‚Äù</a><a href="#fnref7">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn8"><p>See the <a href="#asuka-mari">storyboard</a> of that scene.<a href="#fnref8">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn9"><p>‚ÄúCorrect me if I‚Äôm wrong, but isn‚Äôt this whole section regarding the scrapped (storyboard) sequence of Mari and Asuka working together in the Entry Plug (of Eva-02?)? Or does it actually refer to the final film product of Mari compared to Asuka?‚Äù <a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=461196#461196">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=461196#461196</a></p>
<p>‚ÄúThis does refer to that storyboarded sequence. Judging from the comments in the other interviews, I think what happened in it was that Mari was given Unit-02 after the sync test (based on Enokido‚Äôs idea) and then Asuka sneaks on board Unit-02 anyway, so after the fight Mari presumably makes some excuse to prevent Asuka from being punished. It was a very strange series of ideas, so I can‚Äôt say I‚Äôm disappointed it didn‚Äôt end up being used!‚Äù http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=461276#461276<a href="#fnref9">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn10"><p>Mari‚Äôs actions during the battle with the 10th angel.<a href="#fnref10">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn11"><p>The editor mentions in the endnotes that Anno is referring to Chizuru Nanbara from <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combattler%20V" title="Wikipedia: Combattler V">Combattler V</a></em>.<a href="#fnref11">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn12"><p>Makoto Kosaka, who also voiced Hiromi Oka from <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aim%20for%20the%20Ace" title="Wikipedia: Aim for the Ace">Aim for the Ace</a></em>.<a href="#fnref12">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn13"><p>Meaning that Kaji feeds Shinji with chopsticks‚Ä¶!<a href="#fnref13">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn14"><p>In the video ‚ÄúHideaki Anno talks to kids‚Äù, Anno expresses little interest in food and lists a restricted diet (as one might expect of an animator). It is interesting to compare his newfound interest to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goro%20Miyazaki" title="Wikipedia: Goro Miyazaki">Goro Miyazaki</a>; from <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/10/movies/studio-ghiblis-from-up-on-poppy-hill.html">‚ÄúGrounding a Romance in Memories‚Äù</a>, 7 March 2013:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Home-cooked meals play a significant role in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/From%20Up%20on%20Poppy%20Hill" title="Wikipedia: From Up on Poppy Hill"><em>Poppy Hill</em></a>. Umi is usually the one responsible for making meals at the boardinghouse where she lives with her grandmother, siblings and other residents. In an early scene she prepares rice and eggs for breakfast. In other scenes she shops for food. And the lunches she takes to school are the envy of her classmates: mouthwatering concoctions like an obento box, including cod roe, pickled plum, Japanese omelets and spinach with sesame dressing. ‚ÄúTo eat is to live, and animated characters can‚Äôt really come to life if they don‚Äôt feel alive,‚Äù Mr. [Goro] Miyazaki said. ‚ÄúSo eating was something I looked very closely at. How characters eat can tell you a lot about them. And while they‚Äôre eating, what they‚Äôre thinking at the time can be expressed too.‚Äù Mr.¬†Miyazaki included a number of eating scenes but said it wasn‚Äôt until he finished the film that he fully realized the importance of food in it.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>‚ÄìEditor<a href="#fnref14">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn15"><p>Someone with a license who doesn‚Äôt drive.<a href="#fnref15">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn16"><p><em>sakkasei</em><a href="#fnref16">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn17"><p><em>Sakuga</em> is an animation term which generally refers to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/key%20frames" title="Wikipedia: key frames">key frames</a>, top animators who do them, and the scenes themselves which are generally particularly important or striking movements or actions. ‚ÄìEditor<a href="#fnref17">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn18"><p>The fossil monster <a href="http://ultra.wikia.com/wiki/Stegon">Stegon</a>, which appears in episode 10 (‚ÄúThe Dinosaur Explosion Directive‚Äù) of the <em>tokusatsu</em> series <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The%20Return%20of%20Ultraman" title="Wikipedia: The Return of Ultraman">The Return of Ultraman</a></em>. A dinosaur fossil discovered at a construction site revives as a skeletal monster.<a href="#fnref18">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn19"><p>Among <em>tokusatsu</em> staff, the department which causes the activity of non-human actors such as miniatures. In the case of a monster costume, they control those parts which do not conform to the human body, such as a long neck, tail, or wings, using hanging wires (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/piano%20wire" title="Wikipedia: piano wire">piano wire</a>). In ‚ÄúPrelude‚Äù, the fifth angel was also depicted according to the concept of [an apparently] wire-utilizing ‚Äú<em>souen</em> style‚Äù CG.<a href="#fnref19">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn20"><p>A number of radically-designed pavilions in the 1970 Osaka World‚Äôs Fair were created according to an architectural school of thought called ‚ÄúMetabolism‚Äù which had been put forth by a then-young group of architects. The Toshiba IHI pavilion, designed by Kisho Kurokawa, was a typical example, a structure of linked tetrahedral units made of black iron. [For images &amp; links, see the later discussion of the Toshiba IHI pavilion. ‚ÄìEditor]<a href="#fnref20">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn21"><p>Mecha which appear in great numbers and tend to support or be destroyed by the main characters. ‚ÄìEditor<a href="#fnref21">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn22"><p>An example of the mosaic effect can be seen at <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k4fnpmJBbUQ#t=0m44s">0:45 in a trailer</a>, or <a href="http://img546.imageshack.us/img546/3639/shieldh.jpg">shield</a> and <a href="http://img194.imageshack.us/img194/2544/rudder.jpg">steering</a> screenshots. ‚ÄìEditor<a href="#fnref22">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn23"><p>The SF novel <em>Japan Sinks</em> has had considerable influence over the years. In particular, Yasuhiro Takeda mentions in his <a href="../docs/2002-notenki-memoirs"><em>The Notenki Memoirs</em></a> that the novel author <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sakyo%20Komatsu" title="Wikipedia: Sakyo Komatsu">Sakyo Komatsu</a> often worked with him and other Gainaxers on SF events; Hideaki Anno was <a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/post/491054/Why-does-NGE-have-so-many-references-to-the-Bible/#491054">interviewed by him</a> in 1999 or 2000; and the book comes up in Toshio <a href="../docs/2004-okada">Okada‚Äôs 2004 roundtable</a> &amp; Sawaragi‚Äôs <a href="../docs/2005-sawaragi">2005 essay</a>. ‚ÄìEditor<a href="#fnref23">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn24"><p>This refers to the color of everything going red when the dummy plug is activated in episode 18. ‚ÄúPara‚Äù is short for ‚Äúparaffin‚Äù. ‚ÄìEditor<a href="#fnref24">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn25"><p>The specific part is probably <a href="http://wiki.evageeks.org/File:Proposal_07_apostolos.jpg">page 07</a>, ‚ÄúEva-01 faces off against the Apostolo Sahaquiel. (Original drawing by Yo Yoshinari; painting by Sadamoto.)‚Äù and <a href="http://wiki.evageeks.org/images/4/41/Proposal_31_battles.jpg">page 31</a>, ‚ÄúApostolo Sahaquiel (Angel of the Sky), wheeling over Tokyo-3‚Äù against an spear-wielding Evangelion. ‚ÄìEditor<a href="#fnref25">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn26"><p>Refers, I think, to deciding which parts of an image or design will be colored what color. ‚ÄìEditor<a href="#fnref26">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn27"><p>Pivot Turn: Designates a maneuver where, by having the treads on both sides of a tank or piece of heavy machinery roll in opposite directions at exactly the same speed, the body can turn in any direction without moving [forwards or backwards]. <em>Ritai</em> refers to treads that allow the traversal of uneven ground. They are also called crawler or caterpillar [treads]; however, the widely known name ‚Äúcaterpillar‚Äù is a registered trademark.<a href="#fnref27">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn28"><p>Trolley System: A system whereby electricity can be gathered from aerial wires using a power collector mounted on the roof of a train car, such as a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/pantograph" title="Wikipedia: pantograph">pantograph</a>. Also called ‚Äúaerial wire power collection system.‚Äù<a href="#fnref28">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn29"><p>R-type Missile: A modified version of the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R-7%20%28rocket%20family%29" title="Wikipedia: R-7 (rocket family)">R-7 missile</a>, the A-2 rocket, has been used for the launching of Russian spacecrafts such as the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soyuz" title="Wikipedia: Soyuz">Soyuz</a>.<a href="#fnref29">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn30"><p>Producing the Yamato Model Design: Hideaki Anno sought a [physical] image of his ideal Space Battleship Yamato, and realized it through a Shoichi Manabe prototype. Through the co-operation of the Bandai Visual and Bandai Hobby divisions [of Bandai], it was made into a 30cm long plastic model and included as an extra in the ‚ÄúSpace Battleship Yamato TV DVD-Box,‚Äù which went on sale in February 2008. In the release materials the following words of chief [model] supervisor Hideaki Anno are recorded. ‚ÄúWith this model I was finally able to give form to the images I preserved [within myself] of the Yamato‚Äôs hull - the image [of the Yamato] in the opening sequence, especially where the camera pulls back from the Captain‚Äôs cabin; the full side-image of the Yamato as it launches in episode 3, and the identical double-page spread in black and white from the Yamato illustrated guide; the image from the full-color pullout from the Yamato illustrated guide [?]; the color cover image from the March issue of Boken-o [‚ÄúKing of Adventure‚Äù manga magazine]; and so on.‚Äù<a href="#fnref30">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn31"><p>A competitor to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Body%20Worlds" title="Wikipedia: Body Worlds">Body Worlds</a>; <a href="http://web.archive.org/web/20110519202906/http://jintai.co.jp/index_top.html">archived homepage</a>.<a href="#fnref31">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
<li id="fn32"><p>ÂÖ¨ÈñãÂâç„Å´È∂¥Â∑ªÔºàÂíåÂìâÔºâ„Åï„Çì„Å´ÂèñÊùê„Åó„Åü„Å®„Åç,„Äå„Ç®„É¥„Ç°„Äç„ÇíÁ†¥Â£ä„Åô„Çã„Å´„ÅÇ„Åü„Å£„Å¶Ê¶éÊà∏„Åï„Çì„ÅÆ„Ç¢„Ç§„Éá„Ç¢„ÅåÈöèÊâÄ„Å´Áõõ„ÇäËæº„Åæ„Çå„Å¶„ÅÑ„Çã„Å®„ÅÜ„Åã„Åå„Å£„Åü„ÅÆ„Åß,ËààÂë≥„Åå„ÅÇ„Çä„Åæ„Åô„ÄÇ<a href="#fnref32">‚Ü©</a></p></li>
